# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: air-quality-index
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acid rain has been shown to have adverse impacts on forests, freshwaters, soils, microbes, insects and aquatic life-forms.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In ecosystems, persistent acid rain negatively affects tree bark, leaving trees more susceptible to environmental stressors such as drought, fire, solar radiation, frost and pest infestation.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acid rain is also capable of detrimenting soil composition by stripping it of nutrients such as calcium and magnesium which play a critical role in plant growth and maintaining healthy soil.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In terms of human infrastructure, acid rain also causes the peeling of paint, corrosion of steel structures, and weathering of stone buildings and statues as well as having impacts on human health.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Some governments, including those in Europe and North America, have made efforts since the 1970s to reduce the release of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide into the atmosphere through air pollution regulations such as the US Clean Air Act and the EU Ambient Air Quality Directive.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] These efforts have had positive results due to the widespread research on acid rain starting in the 1960s and the publicized information on its harmful effects.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The main source of sulfur and nitrogen compounds that result in acid rain are anthropogenic, but nitrogen oxides can also be produced naturally by lightning strikes and sulfur dioxide is produced by volcanic eruptions.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acid rain is rain with a pH less than 5.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] A variety of natural and human-made sources contribute to the acidity of precipitations.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] For example nitric acid is produced by electric discharges in the atmosphere such as in lightnings.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The usual anthropogenic sources of acid deposition are sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] They react with water (as does carbon dioxide) to give solutions with pH < 5.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Occasional pH readings in rain and fog water of well below 2.4 have been reported in industrialized areas.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acid rain was first systematically studied in Europe in the 1960s, in the United States and Canada in 1970s, and in India in the late 1980s.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The corrosive effect of polluted, acidic air of London on limestone and marble was noted in the 17th century by John Evelyn, who remarked upon the poor condition of the Arundel marbles.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Since the Industrial Revolution, emissions of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides into the atmosphere have increased.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In 1852, Robert Angus Smith was the first to show the relationship between acid rain and atmospheric pollution in Manchester, England.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Smith coined the term "acid rain" in 1872.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] As soon as the 1960s, European scientists began widely observing and studying the phenomenon.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In 1955 two Swedish scientists had already quoted that "the precipitation over Sweden as a whole is definitely more acid than the CO2 equilibrium alone would permit".
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] At first, the main focus in this research laid on local effects of acid rain.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Waldemar Christofer Brøgger was the first to acknowledge long-distance transportation of pollutants crossing borders from the United Kingdom to Norway.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Near a century later this problem was systematically studied by Brynjulf Ottar in the 1970s.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Ottar's work was strongly influenced by Swedish soil scientist Svante Odén, who had drawn widespread attention to Europe's acid rain problem in popular newspapers and wrote a landmark paper on the subject in 1968.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The earliest report about acid rain in the United States came from chemical evidence gathered from Hubbard Brook Valley; public awareness of acid rain in the US increased in the 1970s after *The New York Times* reported on these findings.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In 1972, a group of scientists, including Gene Likens, discovered the rain that was deposited at White Mountains of New Hampshire was acidic.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The pH of the sample was measured to be 4.03 at Hubbard Brook.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The Hubbard Brook Ecosystem Study followed up with a series of research studies that analyzed the environmental effects of acid rain.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The alumina from soils neutralized acid rain that mixed with stream water at Hubbard Brook.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The result of this research indicated that the chemical reaction between acid rain and aluminium leads to an increasing rate of soil weathering.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Experimental research examined the effects of increased acidity in streams on ecological species.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In 1980, scientists modified the acidity of Norris Brook, New Hampshire, and observed the change in species' behaviors.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] There was a decrease in species diversity, an increase in community dominants, and a reduction in the food web complexity.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In 1980, the US Congress passed an Acid Deposition Act.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] This Act established an 18-year assessment and research program under the direction of the National Acid Precipitation Assessment Program (NAPAP).
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] NAPAP enlarged a network of monitoring sites to determine how acidic precipitation was, seeking to determine long-term trends, and established a network for dry deposition.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Using a statistically based sampling design, NAPAP quantified the effects of acid rain on a regional basis by targeting research and surveys to identify and quantify the impact of acid precipitation on freshwater and terrestrial ecosystems.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] NAPAP also assessed the effects of acid rain on historical buildings, monuments, and building materials.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] It also funded extensive studies on atmospheric processes and potential control programs.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] From the start, policy advocates from all sides attempted to influence NAPAP activities to support their particular policy advocacy efforts, or to disparage those of their opponents.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] For the US Government's scientific enterprise, a significant impact of NAPAP were lessons learned in the assessment process and in environmental research management to a relatively large group of scientists, program managers, and the public.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In 1981, the National Academy of Sciences was looking into research about the controversial issues regarding acid rain, in particular the role of fossil fuel combustion.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] President Ronald Reagan dismissed the issues of acid rain until his personal visit to Canada and confirmed that the Canadian border suffered from the drifting pollution from smokestacks originating in the US Midwest.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Reagan honored the agreement to Canadian Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau's enforcement of anti-pollution regulation.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In 1982, Reagan commissioned William Nierenberg to serve on the National Science Board.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Nierenberg selected scientists including Gene Likens to serve on a panel to draft a report on acid rain.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In 1983, the panel of scientists came up with a draft report, which concluded that acid rain is a real problem and solutions should be sought.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] White House Office of Science and Technology Policy reviewed the draft report and sent Fred Singer's suggestions of the report, which cast doubt on the anthropic causes of acid rain.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The panelists revealed rejections against Singer's positions and submitted the report to Nierenberg in April.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In May 1983, the House of Representatives voted against legislation controlling sulfur emissions.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] There was a debate about whether Nierenberg delayed the release of the report.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Nierenberg denied the saying about his suppression of the report and stated that it was withheld after the House's vote because it was not ready to be published.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In 1991, the US National Acid Precipitation Assessment Program (NAPAP) provided its first assessment of acid rain in the United States.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] It reported that 5% of New England lakes were acidic, with sulfates being the most common problem.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] They noted that 2% of the lakes could no longer support Brook Trout, and 6% of the lakes were unsuitable for the survival of many minnow species.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Subsequent *Reports to Congress* have documented chemical changes in soil and freshwater ecosystems, nitrogen saturation, soil nutrient decreases, episodic acidification, regional haze, and damage to historical monuments.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Meanwhile, in 1990, the US Congress passed a series of amendments to the Clean Air Act.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Title IV of these amendments established a cap and trade system designed to control emissions of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Both these emissions proved to cause a significant problem for U.S. citizens and their access to healthy, clean air.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Title IV called for a total reduction of about 10 million tons of SO2 emissions from power plants, close to a 50% reduction.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Phase I began in 1995 and limited sulfur dioxide emissions from 110 of the largest power plants to 8.7 million tons of sulfur dioxide.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] One power plant in New England (Merrimack) was in Phase I.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Four other plants (Newington, Mount Tom, Brayton Point, and Salem Harbor) were added under other program provisions.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Phase II began in 2000 and affects most of the power plants in the country.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] On March 10, 2005, the EPA issued the Clean Air Interstate Rule (CAIR).
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] This rule provides states with a solution to the problem of power plant pollution that drifts from one state to another.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] CAIR will permanently cap emissions of SO2 and NOx in the eastern United States.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] CAIR hoped to reduce SO2 emissions in 28 eastern states and the District of Columbia by over 70% and NOx emissions by over 60% from 2003 levels.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] CAIR was replaced by the Cross-State Air Pollution Rule (CSAPR), as of 1 January 2015.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Overall, the program's cap and trade program has been successful in achieving its goals.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Since the 1990s, SO2 emissions have dropped 40%, and according to the Pacific Research Institute, acid rain levels have dropped 65% since 1976.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Conventional regulation was used in the European Union, which saw a decrease of over 70% in SO2 emissions during the same period.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In 2007, total SO2 emissions were 8.9 million tons, achieving the program's long-term goal ahead of the 2010 statutory deadline.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In 2007 the EPA estimated that by 2010, the overall costs of complying with the program for businesses and consumers would be $1 billion to $2 billion a year, only one-fourth of what was initially predicted.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Forbes says: "In 2010, by which time the cap and trade system had been augmented by the George W.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The term citizen science can be traced back as far as January 1989 to a campaign by the Audubon Society to measure acid rain, with 280 volunteers nationwide, all members of the Audubon Society, making a one-year commitment to collect and measure the pH of precipitation samples.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Canadian Harold Harvey was among the first to research a "dead" lake.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In 1972, he and Richard Beamish documented the gradual deterioration of fish stocks in 60 lakes in Killarney Park in Ontario, which they had been studying systematically since 1966.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In the 1970s and 80s, acid rain was a major topic of research at the Experimental Lakes Area (ELA) in Northwestern Ontario, Canada.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Researchers added sulfuric acid to whole lakes in controlled ecosystem experiments to simulate the effects of acid rain.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Because its remote conditions allowed for whole-ecosystem experiments, research at the ELA showed that the effect of acid rain on fish populations started at concentrations much lower than those observed in laboratory experiments.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In the context of a complete food web, fish populations crashed earlier than when acid rain had direct toxic effects to the fish because the acidity led to crashes in prey populations (e.g. mysids).
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] As experimental acid inputs were reduced, fish populations and lake ecosystems recovered at least partially, although invertebrate populations have still not completely returned to the baseline conditions.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] This research showed both that acidification was linked to declining fish populations and that the effects could be reversed if sulfuric acid emissions decreased, and influenced policy in Canada and the United States.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In 1985, seven Canadian provinces (all except British Columbia, Alberta, and Saskatchewan) and the federal government signed the Eastern Canada Acid Rain Program.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The provinces agreed to limit their combined sulfur dioxide emissions to 2.3 million tonnes by 1994.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The US-Canada Air Quality Agreement was signed in 1991.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In 1998, all federal, provincial, and territorial Ministers of Energy and Environment signed The Canada-Wide Acid Rain Strategy for Post-2000, which was designed to protect lakes that are more sensitive than those protected by earlier policies.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acid rain was first reported in Mumbai (then Bombay) in 1974.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acid rain has been a reported cause of decrease in soil pH, especially in the northeast region, as well as the coastal regions of Karnataka, Kerala, Odisha, Bihar, and West Bengal.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The spread of acid rain over India was first studied by a team of researchers in 1989.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Increased risk might be posed by the expected rise in total sulphur emissions from 4,400 kilotonnes (kt) in 1990 to 6,500 kt in 2000, 10,900 kt in 2010 and 18,500 in 2020.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Damage to Taj Mahal is a popular example of acid rain's corrosive effect in India.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] India is the largest sulphur emitter, mostly from coal-fired power plants.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] On 11 July 2025, the Indian government changed its own rules, exempting most coal-fired power plants from installing technology to reduce sulphur dioxide (SO2) emissions, reversing a key environmental policy launched in 2015 to cut sulphur emissions.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In China, concern about the possible effects of acid rain emerged later than in Europe and North America.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The first reports in the international literature regarding acid rain in China appeared in the 1980s.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] A major cause of acid rain in China is the extensive use of coal, which in 2004 accounted for 69% of the energy production.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] However, a great need still exists for better monitoring of the environmental situation in China to support policy development and follow-up on emission reduction measures.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The most important gas which leads to acidification is sulfur dioxide.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] However, emissions of nitrogen oxides (NOx) and ammonia which are further oxidized to form nitric acid are of increasing importance due to stricter controls on emissions of sulfur compounds and the near absence of control on acid rain gasses emitted by intensive farming.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] 70 Tg(S) per year in the form of SO2 comes from fossil fuel combustion and industry, 2.8 Tg(S) from wildfires, and 7–8 Tg(S) per year from volcanoes.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The principal natural phenomena that contribute acid-producing gases to the atmosphere are emissions from volcanoes.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acid-producing gases are also created by biological processes that occur in wetlands and the oceans.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The major biological source of atmospheric sulfur compounds is dimethyl sulfide.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Nitric acid is also produced by electrical activity in the atmosphere such as lightning.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Despite its toxicity, and negative effects of low pH, nitric acid in rainwater is an important source of fixed nitrogen for plant life.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acidic sulfate deposits associated with tephra have been detected in glacial ice thousands of years old in remote parts of the globe, suggesting that volcanism was the main agent of rain acidification before the Anthropocene.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The principal cause of present-day acid rain is sulfur and nitrogen compounds from human sources, such as coal-fired power stations, animal agriculture, fertilizers, steel mills, and motor vehicles.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Power plants account for a quarter of nitrogen oxides (NOx) and two-thirds of sulfur dioxide within the atmosphere.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Industrial acid rain is still a substantial problem in China and Russia and areas downwind from them.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] These areas all burn sulfur-containing coal to generate heat and electricity.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The problem of acid rain has not only increased with population and industrial growth, but has become more widespread.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The use of tall smokestacks to reduce local pollution has contributed to the spread of acid rain by releasing gases into regional atmospheric circulation; dispersal from these taller stacks causes pollutants to be carried farther, causing widespread ecological damage.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Often deposition occurs a considerable distance downwind of the emissions, with mountainous regions tending to receive the greatest deposition because of their higher rainfall and direct contact with long-distance transported clouds.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] An example of this effect is the low pH of rain which falls in Scandinavia.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acid rain falls at a pH value of roughly 4, making it harmful to consume for humans, plants, microbes and animals.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] When these low pH levels fall in specific regions, they not only affect the environment but also human health.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] With acidic pH levels in humans comes hair loss, low urinary pH, severe mineral deficiency, constipation, and many cases of chronic disorders like fibromyalgia and basal-cell carcinoma.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Combustion of fuels and smelting of some ores produce sulfur dioxide and nitric oxides (NOx).
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] They are converted into sulfuric acid and nitric acid by photochemical reactions in the troposphere.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The detailed mechanisms depend on the presence water and traces of iron and manganese.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] A number of oxidants are capable of these reactions aside from O2, these include ozone, hydrogen peroxide, and oxygen.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Wet deposition of acids occurs when any form of precipitation (e.g. rain, snow, fog) removes acids from the atmosphere and delivers them to the Earth's surface.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] This can result from the deposition of acids produced in the raindrops or by the precipitation removing the acids either in clouds or below clouds.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Wet removal of both gases and aerosols are both of importance for wet deposition.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acid deposition also occurs via dry deposition in the absence of precipitation.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] This can be responsible for as much as 20 to 60% of total acid deposition.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] This occurs when particles and gases stick to the ground, plants or other surfaces.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acid rain has been shown to have adverse impacts on forests, freshwaters and soils, killing terrestrial and aquatic life-forms as well as causing damage to buildings and having impacts on human health.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Sulfuric acid and nitric acid have multiple impacts on aquatic ecosystems, including acidification, increased nitrogen and aluminium content, and alteration of biogeochemical processes.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Both the lower pH and higher aluminium concentrations in surface water that occur as a result of acid rain can cause damage to fish and other aquatic animals as well as to microbes and plants.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] At pH lower than 5 most fish eggs will not hatch and pH lower than 4 will kill adult fish.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] As lakes and rivers become more acidic, biodiversity is reduced, while it is less affected in regions where freshwater is naturally acid.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acid rain has eliminated insect life and some fish species, including the brook trout in some lakes, streams, and creeks in geographically sensitive areas, such as the Adirondack Mountains of the United States.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] However, the extent to which acid rain contributes directly or indirectly via runoff from the catchment to lake and river acidity (i.e., depending on characteristics of the surrounding watershed) is variable.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The United States Environmental Protection Agency's (EPA) website states: "Of the lakes and streams surveyed, acid rain caused acidity in 75% of the acidic lakes and about 50% of the acidic streams".
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Lakes hosted by silicate basement rocks are more acidic than lakes within limestone or other basement rocks with a carbonate composition (i.e. marble) due to buffering effects by carbonate minerals, even with the same amount of acid rain.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Soil biology and chemistry can be seriously damaged by acid rain.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Some microbes are unable to tolerate changes to low pH and are killed.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The enzymes of these microbes are denatured (changed in shape so they no longer function) by the acid, with attending collapse in soil functions (e.g. decomposition).
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The hydronium ions of acid rain also mobilize toxins, such as aluminium, and leach away essential nutrients and minerals such as magnesium.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Soil chemistry can be dramatically changed when base cations, such as calcium and magnesium, are leached by acid rain, thereby affecting sensitive tree species, such as sugar maple (*Acer saccharum*).
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Impacts of acidic water and soil acidification on plants could be minor or in most cases major.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Most minor cases which do not result in fatality of plant life can be attributed to the plants being less susceptible to acidic conditions and/or the acid rain being less potent.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] However, even in minor cases, the plant will eventually die due to the acidic water lowering the plant's natural pH.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acidic water enters the plant and causes important plant minerals to dissolve and get carried away; which ultimately causes the plant to die of lack of minerals for nutrition.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In major cases, which are more extreme, the same process of damage occurs as in minor cases, which is removal of essential minerals, but at a much quicker rate.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Likewise, acid rain that falls on soil and on plant leaves causes drying of the waxy leaf cuticle, which ultimately causes rapid water loss from the plant to the outside atmosphere and eventually results in death of the plant.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Soil acidification can lead to a decline in soil microbes as a result of a change in pH, which would have an adverse effect on plants due to their dependence on soil microbes to access nutrients.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] To see if a plant is being affected by soil acidification, one can closely observe the plant leaves.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] If the leaves are green and look healthy, the soil pH is normal and acceptable for plant life.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] But if the plant leaves have yellowing between the veins on their leaves, that means the plant is suffering from acidification and is unhealthy.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Moreover, a plant suffering from soil acidification cannot photosynthesize; the acid-water-induced process of drying out of the plant can destroy chloroplast organelles.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Without being able to photosynthesize, a plant cannot create nutrients for its own survival or oxygen for the survival of aerobic organisms, which affects most species on Earth and ultimately ends the purpose of the plant's existence.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] It has been suggested that the collapse of photosynthesis linked to acid rain (caused by the emission of sulfur oxide from intense volcanism) could have contributed to the Permian-Triassic mass extinction.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Adverse effects may be indirectly related to acid rain, like the acid's effects on soil (see above) or the high concentration of gaseous precursors to acid rain.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] High altitude forests are especially vulnerable as they are often surrounded by clouds and fog which are more acidic than rain.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Plants are capable of adapting to acid rain.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] On Jinyun Mountain, Chongqing, plant species were seen adapting to new environmental conditions.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The affects on the species ranged from being beneficial to detrimental.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] With natural rainfall or mild acid rainfall, the biochemical and physiological characteristics of plant seedlings were enhanced.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] However, once the pH decreases below the threshold of 3.5, the acid rain can no longer be beneficial and begins to have negative affects.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acid rain can negatively impact photosynthesis in plant leaves, when leaves are exposed to a lower pH, photosynthesis is impacted due to the decline in chlorophyll.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acid rain also has the ability to cause deformation to leaves at a cellular level, tissue scaring and changes to the stomatal, epidermis and mesophyll cells.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Additional impacts of acid rain includes a decline in cuticle thickness present on the leaf surface.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Because acid rain damages leaves, this directly impacts a plants ability to have a strong canopy cover, a decline in canopy cover can lead plants to be more vulnerable to diseases.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Dead or dying trees (forest dieback) often appear in areas impacted by acid rain, although other factors such as drought stress linked to global warming cannot be excluded, too.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acid rain causes aluminium to leach from the soil, posing risks to both plant and animal life.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Furthermore, it strips the soil of critical minerals and nutrients necessary for tree growth.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] At higher altitudes, acidic fog and clouds can deplete nutrients from tree foliage, leading to discolored or dead leaves and needles, with broadleaved species tending to be more sentitive than conifers.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] This depletion compromises the trees' ability to absorb sunlight, weakening them and diminishing their capacity to endure cold conditions.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Other plants can also be damaged by acid rain, but the effect on food crops is (or should be) minimized by the application of lime and fertilizers to replace lost nutrients.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In cultivated areas, limestone may also be added to increase the ability of the soil to keep the pH stable through the buffering effect of calcium carbonate, but this tactic is largely unusable in the case of wilderness lands.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] When calcium is leached from the needles of red spruce, these trees become less cold tolerant and exhibit winter injury and even death.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acid rain may also affect crop productivity by necrosis or changes to soil nutrients, which ultimately prevent plants from reaching maturity.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acid rain has a much less harmful effect on oceans on a global scale, but it creates an amplified impact in the shallower waters of coastal waters.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acid rain can cause the ocean's pH to fall, known as ocean acidification, making it more difficult for different coastal species to create their exoskeletons that they need to survive and escape predation.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] These coastal species link together as part of the ocean's food chain, and without them being a source for other marine life to feed off of, more marine life will die.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Coral's limestone skeleton is particularly sensitive to pH decreases, because the calcium carbonate, a core component of the limestone skeleton, dissolves in acidic (low pH) solutions.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In addition to acidification, excess nitrogen inputs from the atmosphere promote increased growth of phytoplankton and other marine plants, which, in turn, may cause more frequent harmful algal blooms and eutrophication (the creation of oxygen-depleted "dead zones") in some parts of the ocean.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] However, some studies on intertidal zones point to the prominence of acid rain as a cause of the observed decline in algal species richness.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acid rain can negatively impact human health, especially when people breathe in particles released from acid rain.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The effects of acid rain on human health are complex and may be seen in several ways , such as respiratory issues for long-term exposure and indirect exposure through contaminated food and water sources.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Exposure to air pollutants associated with acid rain, such as nitrogen dioxide (NO2), may have a negative impact on respiratory health.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Water-soluble nitrogen dioxide accumulates in the tiny lung airways (bronchioles), where it is transformed into nitric and nitrous acids, causing damage to the cells of the respiratory tract by various mechanisms.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Pneumonia caused by nitric acids directly damages the epithelial cells lining the airways, resulting in pulmonary edema.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Exposure to nitrogen dioxide also reduces the immune response by inhibiting the generation of inflammatory cytokines by alveolar macrophages in response to bacterial infection, and more particularly in smokers.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The pollutant further reduces respiratory immunity by decreasing mucociliary clearance in the lower respiratory tract, which results in a reduced ability to remove respiratory infections.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The effects of sulfur trioxide and sulfuric acid are similar because the former produces sulfuric acid when it comes into touch with the wet surfaces of your skin or respiratory system.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The amount of SO3 breath through the mouth is larger than the amount of SO3 breath through the nose.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] When humans breathe in sulfur trioxide, small droplets of sulfuric acid will form inside the body and enter the respiratory tract to the lungs depending on the particle size.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The effects of SO3 on the respiratory system lead to breathing difficulty in people who have asthma symptoms.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Sulfur trioxide also causes very corrosive and irritation on the skin, eye, and gastrointestinal tracts when there is direct exposure to a specific concentration or long-term exposure.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Consuming concentrated sulfuric acid has been known to burn the mouth and throat, erode a hole in the stomach, burns when it comes into contact with skin, make your eyes weep if it gets into them, and mortality.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] A 25 parts per million (ppm) maximum for nitrogen oxides (NOx) in working air has been set by the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) for an 8-hour workday and a 40-hour workweek.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Additionally, OSHA has established a 5-ppm nitrogen dioxide exposure limit for 15 minutes in the workplace.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The not-to-exceed limits in the air, water, soil, or food that are recommended by US regulations are often based on levels that affect animals before being modified to assist in safeguarding people.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Depending on whether they employ different animal studies, have different exposure lengths (e.g., an 8-hour workday versus a 24-hour day), or for other reasons, these not-to-exceed values can vary between federal bodies.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The amount of sulfur dioxide that can be emitted into the atmosphere is capped by the EPA.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] This reduces the quantity of sulfur dioxide in the air that turns into sulfur trioxide and sulfuric acid.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Sulfuric acid concentrations in workroom air are restricted by OSHA to 1 mg/m3.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Moreover, NIOSH advises a time-weighted average limit of 1 mg/m3.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acid rain can damage buildings, historic monuments, and statues, especially those made of carbonate rocks, such as limestone and marble.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acids in the rain react with the calcium compounds in the stones to create gypsum, which then flakes off.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The effects of this are commonly seen on old gravestones, where acid rain can cause the inscriptions to become completely illegible.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acid rain also increases the corrosion rate of metals, in particular iron, steel, copper and bronze.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Places significantly impacted by acid rain around the globe include most of eastern Europe from Poland northward into Scandinavia, the eastern third of the United States, and southeastern Canada.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Other affected areas include the southeastern coast of China (the Minnan Golden Triangle) and Taiwan.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Many coal-firing power stations use flue-gas desulfurization (FGD) to remove sulfur-containing gases from their stack gases.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] For a typical coal-fired power station, FGD will remove 95% or more of the SO2 in the flue gases.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] An example of FGD is the wet scrubber which is commonly used.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] A wet scrubber is basically a reaction tower equipped with a fan that extracts hot smoke stack gases from a power plant into the tower.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Lime or limestone in slurry form is also injected into the tower to mix with the stack gases and combine with the sulfur dioxide present.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The calcium carbonate of the limestone produces pH-neutral calcium sulfate that is physically removed from the scrubber.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] That is, the scrubber turns sulfur dioxide pollution into industrial sulfates.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] FGD gypsum is used in construction materials (e.g. concrete), and instead of natural gypsum it can be added to agricultural soils as a source of high-quality sulfur and calcium.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Fluidized bed combustion also reduces the amount of sulfur emitted by power production.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Vehicle emissions control reduces emissions of nitrogen oxides from motor vehicles, but measures are required to further reduce road transport emissions, more especially in Diesel vehicles.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Acid rain is now as severe a threat to the developing world, especially India and China, as it was earlier to some of the developed countries.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] International treaties on the long-range transport of atmospheric pollutants have been agreed upon by western countries for some time now.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Beginning in 1979, European countries convened in order to ratify general principles discussed during the UNECE Convention on Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The purpose was to combat long-range transboundary air pollution.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The 1985 Helsinki Protocol on the Reduction of Sulphur Emissions under the Convention on Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution furthered the results of the Convention.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Results of the treaty have already come to fruition, as evidenced by emissions of particulate matter and sulphur dropping by 30-80% since 1990 in Europe and by 30-40% in North America.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The effectiveness of the Convention in combatting acid rain has inspired further acts of international commitment to prevent the proliferation of atmospheric pollution.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Canada and the US signed the Air Quality Agreement in 1991.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Most European countries and Canada signed the treaties.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Activity of the Convention on Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution remained dormant after 1999, when 27 countries convened to further reduce the effects of acid rain.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In 2000, foreign cooperation to prevent acid rain was sparked in Asia for the first time.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Ten diplomats from countries ranging throughout the continent convened to discuss ways to prevent acid rain.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Following these discussions, the Acid Deposition Monitoring Network in East Asia (EANET) was established in 2001 as an intergovernmental initiative to provide science-based inputs for decision makers and promote international cooperation on acid deposition in East Asia.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In 2023, the EANET member countries include Cambodia, China, Indonesia, Japan, Laos, Malaysia, Mongolia, Myanmar, Philippines, South Korea, Russia, Thailand and Vietnam.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] In this regulatory scheme, every current polluting facility is given or may purchase on an open market an emission allowance for each unit of a designated pollutant it emits.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] Operators can then install pollution control equipment, and sell portions of their emission allowances they no longer need for their own operations, thereby recovering some of the capital cost of their investment in such equipment.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The intention is to give operators economic incentives to install pollution controls.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] However, ethical arguments have been opposed to the ongoing rise of emissions trading, focusing on commodification of the atmosphere, pricing that which should not be priced, or civic responsibility.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The first emissions trading market was established in the United States by enactment of the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] The overall goal of the Acid Rain Program established by the Act is to achieve significant environmental and public health benefits through reductions in emissions of sulfur dioxide (SO2) and nitrogen oxides (NOx), the primary causes of acid rain.
[src:air-quality-index/acid-rain] To achieve this goal at the lowest cost to society, the program employs both regulatory and market based approaches for controlling air pollution.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] The actinide series is a group of chemical elements with atomic numbers ranging from 89 to 102, including notable elements such as uranium and plutonium.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] The nuclides (or isotopes) thorium-232, uranium-235, and uranium-238 occur primordially, while trace quantities of actinium, protactinium, neptunium, and plutonium exist as a result of radioactive decay and, in the case of neptunium and plutonium, neutron capture of uranium.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] These elements have much shorter half-lives than the naturally occurring thorium and uranium, and thus are far more radioactive.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Elements with atomic numbers greater than 94 do not exist naturally on Earth, and must be produced in a nuclear reactor.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] However, certain isotopes of elements up to californium (atomic number 98) still have practical applications which take advantage of their radioactive properties.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] While all actinides are radioactive, actinides and their compounds comprise a significant portion of the Earth's crust.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] There is enough thorium and uranium to be commercially mined, with thorium having a concentration in the Earth's crust about four times that of uranium.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] The global production of uranium in 2021 was over six million tons, with Australia having been the leading supplier.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Thorium is extracted as a byproduct of titanium, zirconium, tin, and rare earths from monazite, from which thorium is often a waste product.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Despite its greater abundance in the Earth's crust, the low demand for thorium in comparison to other metals extracted alongside thorium has led to a global surplus.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] The primary hazard associated with actinides is their radioactivity, though they may also cause heavy metal poisoning if absorbed into the bloodstream.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Generally, ingested insoluble actinide compounds, such as uranium dioxide and mixed oxide (MOX) fuel, will pass through the digestive tract with little effect since they have long half-lives, and cannot dissolve and be absorbed into the bloodstream.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Inhaled actinide compounds, however, will be more damaging as they remain in the lungs and irradiate lung tissue.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Actinium can be found naturally in traces in uranium ore as 227Ac, which is an alpha and beta emitter with a half-life of 21.773 years.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Uranium ore contains about 0.2 mg of actinium per ton of uranium.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] It is more commonly made in milligram amounts by neutron irradiation of 226Ra in a nuclear reactor.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Natural actinium almost exclusively consists of one isotope, 227Ac, with only minute traces of other shorter-lived isotopes (225Ac and 228Ac) occurring in other decay chains.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Thorium is found at low levels in most rocks and soils, where it is about three times more abundant than uranium and about as abundant as lead.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] On average, soil commonly contains around 6 parts per million (ppm) thorium.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Thorium occurs in several minerals; the most common is the rare earth-thorium-phosphate mineral monazite, which contains up to 12% thorium oxide, of which several countries have substantial deposits.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] 232Th decays very slowly, with its half-life being 14.0 billion years, about three times the age of the Earth.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Other isotopes of thorium occur in the thorium and uranium decay chains.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] These are shorter-lived and hence much more radioactive than 232Th, though on a mass basis they are negligible.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Thorium has been linked to liver cancer.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] In the past, thoria (thorium dioxide) was used as a contrast agent for medical X-ray radiography, sold under the name Thorotrast.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] In India, a large amount of thorium ore can be found in the form of monazite in placer deposits of the Western and Eastern coastal dune sands, particularly in the Tamil Nadu coastal areas.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] The residents of this area are exposed to a naturally occurring radiation dose ten times higher than the worldwide average.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Protactinium is one of the rarest and most expensive naturally occurring elements.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] It is found in the form of two isotopes, 231Pa and 234Pa, with the isotope 234Pa occurring in two different energy states.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Nearly all natural protactinium is 231Pa.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] It is an alpha emitter and is formed by the decay of uranium-235, whereas the beta-radiating 234Pa is produced as a result of uranium-238 decay.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Nearly all uranium-238 (99.8%) decays first to the shorter-lived 234mPa isomer.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Protactinium occurs in uraninite (pitchblende) at concentrations of about 0.3–3 parts 231Pa per million parts (ppm) of ore.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Whereas the usual content is closer to 0.3 ppm(e.g. in Jáchymov, Czech Republic), some ores from the Democratic Republic of the Congo have about 3 ppm.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Protactinium is homogeneously dispersed in most natural materials and in water, but at much lower concentrations on the order of one part per trillion, corresponding to a radioactivity of 0.1 picocuries (pCi)/g.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] There is about 500 times more protactinium in sandy soil particles than in water, even when compared to water present in the same sample of soil.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Much higher ratios of 2,000 and above are measured in loam soils and clays, such as bentonite.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] It is more plentiful than antimony, beryllium, cadmium, gold, mercury, silver, or tungsten, and is about as abundant as arsenic or molybdenum.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Significant concentrations of uranium occur in some substances such as phosphate rock deposits, minerals such as lignite, and monazite sands in uranium-rich ores, where it is also commercially extracted from.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Seawater contains about 3.3 parts per billion of uranium by weight as uranium (VI), which forms soluble carbonate complexes.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Extraction of uranium from seawater has been considered as a means of obtaining the element.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Because of the very low specific activity of uranium, the chemical effects of it upon living things can often outweigh the effects of its radioactivity.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Additional uranium has been added to the environment in some locations from the nuclear fuel cycle and the use of depleted uranium in munitions.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Neptunium can be found naturally in low concentrations in uranium ore, where atoms of uranium-238 capture neutrons and undergo transmutation reactions, resulting in neptunium-237 and neptunium-239.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Despite this, it is relatively mobile over the long term, and diffusion of 237Np in groundwater is a major issue in designing a deep geological repository for permanent storage of spent nuclear fuel.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] 237Np has a half-life of 2.144 million years and is therefore a long-term problem; its half-life is still much shorter than those of uranium-238, uranium-235, or uranium-236, and therefore 237Np has higher specific activity than those nuclides.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] It is used only to make plutonium-238 when bombarded with neutrons in a lab.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Plutonium occurs naturally in low concentrations in uranium ore.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Plutonium-238 is a product of the double beta decay of uranium-238, and plutonium-239 is a decay product of neptunium-239, which occurs when 238U undergoes a transmutation reaction due to neutron capture.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Plutonium-240 and plutonium-244 can also be found in nature, of which the latter's half-life of 81.3 million years has had it be suggested as a primordial radionuclide, though early reports of its detection could not be confirmed.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Plutonium has many applications, and through these applications, trace amounts of plutonium have been released into the environment.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Plutonium, like other actinides, readily forms a dioxide.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] In the environment, this plutonyl readily complexes with carbonate as well as other oxygen moieties (OH−, NO2−, NO3−, and SO42−) to form charged complexes which can be readily mobile with low affinities to soil.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] PuO2 formed from neutralizing highly acidic nitric acid solutions tends to form polymeric PuO2 which is resistant to complexation.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Plutonium also readily shifts valences between the +3, +4, +5 and +6 states.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] It is common for some fraction of plutonium in solution to exist in all of these states in equilibrium.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Like neptunium, plutonium is known to bind to soil particles very strongly.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] While caesium has very different chemistry from the actinides, it is well known that both caesium and many actinides bind strongly to the minerals in soil.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] It has been possible to use 134Cs-labeled soil to study the migration of Pu and Cs is soils.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] It has been shown that colloidal transport processes control the migration of Cs (and thus will control the migration of Pu) in the soil at the Waste Isolation Pilot Plant.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Americium often enters landfills from discarded smoke detectors.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] The rules for the disposal of smoke detectors are very relaxed in most municipalities.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] For instance, in the UK it is permissible to dispose of a smoke detector containing americium by placing it in the trash with normal household waste, but each trashcan is limited to only contain one smoke detector.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] The manufacture of products containing americium, as well as nuclear reactors and explosions, may also release americium into the environment.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] In 1999, a truck transporting 900 smoke detectors in France was reported to have caught fire; it is claimed that this led to a release of americium into the environment.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] In the U.S., the "Radioactive Boy Scout" David Hahn was able to buy thousands of smoke detectors at remainder prices and concentrate the americium from them.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] There have been cases of humans being exposed to americium.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] The worst case was that of Harold McCluskey, who was exposed to an extremely high dose of americium-241 after an accident involving a glove box.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] He was subsequently treated with chelation therapy.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] It is likely that the medical care which he was given saved his life; despite similar biodistribution and toxicity to plutonium, the two radioactive elements have different solution-state chemistries.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Americium is stable in the +3 oxidation state, while the +4 oxidation state of plutonium can form in the human body.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] The most common isotope americium-241 decays with a half-life of 432 years to neptunium-237.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] In the long term, the issues discussed above for neptunium apply.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Americium released into the environment tends to remain in soil and water at relatively shallow depths and may be taken up by animals and plants during growth; shellfish such as shrimp take up americium-241 in their shells, and parts of grain plants can become contaminated by exposure.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Chaplin et al. reported advances in the diffusive gradients in thin films technique, which have provided a method to measure labile bioavailable americium in soils, as well as in freshwater and seawater.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Atmospheric curium compounds are poorly soluble in common solvents and mostly adhere to soil particles.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Soil analysis revealed about 4,000 times higher concentration of curium in the sandy soil particles than in water present in the soil pores.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] An even higher ratio of about 18,000 was measured in loam soils.
[src:air-quality-index/actinides-in-the-environment] Californium is fairly insoluble in water, but it adheres well to ordinary soil, and concentrations of it in the soil can be 500 times higher than in the water surrounding the soil particles.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] ARS involves a total dose of greater than 0.7 Gy (70 rad), which generally occurs from a source outside the body, delivered within a few minutes.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Sources of such radiation can occur accidentally or intentionally.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] They may involve nuclear reactors, cyclotrons, certain devices used in cancer therapy, nuclear weapons, or radiological weapons.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] It is generally divided into three types: bone marrow, gastrointestinal, and neurovascular syndrome, with bone marrow syndrome occurring at 0.7 to 10 Gy, and neurovascular syndrome occurring at doses that exceed 50 Gy.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The cells that are most affected are generally those that are rapidly dividing.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] At high doses, this causes DNA damage that may be irreparable.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Diagnosis is based on a history of exposure and symptoms.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Repeated complete blood counts (CBCs) can indicate the severity of exposure.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Treatment of ARS is generally supportive care.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] This may include blood transfusions, antibiotics, colony-stimulating factors, or stem cell transplant.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Radioactive material remaining on the skin or in the stomach should be removed.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] If radioiodine was inhaled or ingested, potassium iodide is recommended.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Complications such as leukemia and other cancers among those who survive are managed as usual.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Short-term outcomes depend on the dose exposure.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] A single event can affect a large number of people.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The vast majority of cases involving ARS, alongside blast effects, were inflicted by the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki, with post-attack deaths in the tens of thousands.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Nuclear and radiation accidents and incidents sometimes cause ARS; the worst, the Chernobyl nuclear power plant disaster, caused 134 cases and 28 deaths.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] ARS differs from chronic radiation syndrome, which occurs following prolonged exposures to relatively low doses of radiation, and from radiation-induced cancer.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Classically, ARS is divided into three main presentations: hematopoietic, gastrointestinal, and neurovascular.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] These syndromes may be preceded by a prodrome.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The speed of symptom onset is related to radiation exposure, with greater doses resulting in a shorter delay in symptom onset.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] These presentations presume whole-body exposure, and many of them are markers that are invalid if the entire body has not been exposed.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Each syndrome requires that the tissue showing the syndrome itself be exposed (for instance, gastrointestinal syndrome is not seen if the stomach and intestines are not exposed to radiation).
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] This syndrome often follows absorbed doses of 6–30 grays (600–3,000 rad).
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The signs and symptoms of this form of radiation injury include nausea, vomiting, loss of appetite, and abdominal pain.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Vomiting in this time-frame (1-2h post-exposure) is a marker for whole-body exposures that are in the fatal range above 4 grays (400 rad).
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Without exotic treatment such as bone marrow transplant, death with this dose is common, due generally more to infection than gastrointestinal dysfunction.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] This syndrome typically occurs at absorbed doses greater than 30 grays (3,000 rad), though it may occur at doses as low as 10 grays (1,000 rad).
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] It presents with neurological symptoms such as dizziness, headache, or decreased level of consciousness, occurring within minutes to a few hours, with an absence of vomiting, and is almost always fatal, even with aggressive intensive care.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Early symptoms of ARS typically include nausea, vomiting, headaches, fatigue, fever, and a short period of skin reddening.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] These symptoms may occur at radiation doses as low as 0.35 grays (35 rad).
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] These symptoms are common to many illnesses, and may not, by themselves, indicate acute radiation sickness.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] A person who was less than 1 mile (1.6 km) from the atomic bomb *Little Boy*'s hypocenter at Hiroshima, Japan, was found to have absorbed about 9.46 grays (Gy) of ionizing radiation.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The doses at the hypocenters of the Hiroshima and Nagasaki atomic bombings were 240 and 290 Gy, respectively.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Cutaneous radiation syndrome (CRS) refers to the skin symptoms of radiation exposure.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Within a few hours after irradiation, a transient and inconsistent redness (associated with itching) can occur.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Then, a latent phase may occur and last from a few days up to several weeks, when intense reddening, blistering, and ulceration of the irradiated site is visible.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] In most cases, healing occurs by regenerative means; however, very large skin doses can cause permanent hair loss, damaged sebaceous and sweat glands, atrophy, fibrosis (mostly keloids), decreased or increased skin pigmentation, and ulceration or necrosis of the exposed tissue.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] As seen at Chernobyl, when skin is irradiated with high energy beta particles, moist desquamation (peeling of skin) and similar early effects can heal, only to be followed by the collapse of the dermal vascular system after two months, resulting in the loss of the full thickness of the exposed skin.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Another example of skin loss caused by high-level exposure of radiation is during the 1999 Tokaimura nuclear accident, where technician Hisashi Ouchi had lost a majority of his skin due to the high amounts of radiation he absorbed during the irradiation.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] This effect had been demonstrated previously with pig skin using high energy beta sources at the Churchill Hospital Research Institute, in Oxford.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] ARS is caused by exposure to a large dose of ionizing radiation (> ≈ 0.1 Gy) over a short period of time (> ≈ 0.1 Gy/h).
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Alpha and beta radiation have low penetrating power and are unlikely to affect vital internal organs from outside the body.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Any type of ionizing radiation can cause burns, but alpha and beta radiation can only do so if radioactive contamination or nuclear fallout is deposited on the individual's skin or clothing.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Gamma and neutron radiation can travel much greater distances and penetrate the body easily, so whole-body irradiation generally causes ARS before skin effects are evident.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Local gamma irradiation can cause skin effects without any sickness.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] In the early twentieth century, radiographers would commonly calibrate their machines by irradiating their own hands and measuring the time to onset of erythema.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Accidental exposure may be the result of a criticality or radiotherapy accident.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] There have been numerous criticality accidents dating back to atomic testing during World War II, while computer-controlled radiation therapy machines such as Therac-25 played a major part in radiotherapy accidents.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The latter of the two is caused by the failure of equipment software used to monitor the radiational dose given.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Human error has played a large part in accidental exposure incidents, including some of the criticality accidents, and larger scale events such as the Chernobyl disaster.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Other events have to do with orphan sources, in which radioactive material is unknowingly kept, sold, or stolen.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The Goiânia accident is an example, where a forgotten radioactive source was taken from a hospital, resulting in the deaths of 4 people from ARS.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Theft and attempted theft of radioactive material by clueless thieves has also led to lethal exposure in at least one incident.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Exposure may also come from routine spaceflight and solar flares, which result in radiation effects on earth in the form of solar storms.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] During spaceflight, astronauts are exposed to both galactic cosmic radiation (GCR) and solar particle event (SPE) radiation.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The exposure particularly occurs during flights beyond low Earth orbit (LEO).
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Evidence indicates past SPE radiation levels that would have been lethal for unprotected astronauts.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] GCR levels that might lead to acute radiation poisoning are less well understood.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The latter cause is rarer, with an event possibly occurring during the solar storm of 1859.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Intentional exposure is controversial as it involves the use of nuclear weapons, human experiments, or is given to a victim in an act of murder.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The intentional atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki resulted in tens of thousands of casualties; the survivors of these bombings are known today as *hibakusha*.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Nuclear weapons emit large amounts of thermal radiation as visible, infrared, and ultraviolet light, to which the atmosphere is largely transparent.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] This event is also known as "flash", where radiant heat and light are bombarded into any given victim's exposed skin, causing radiation burns.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Death is highly likely, and radiation poisoning is almost certain if one is caught in the open with no terrain or building masking-effects within a radius of 0–3 km from a 1 megaton airburst.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The 50% chance of death from the blast extends out to ≈ 8 km from a 1 megaton atmospheric explosion.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Scientific testing on humans within the United States occurred extensively throughout the atomic age.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Experiments took place on a range of subjects including, but not limited to; the disabled, children, soldiers, and incarcerated persons, with the level of understanding and consent given by subjects varying from complete to none.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Since 1997 there have been requirements for patients to give informed consent, and to be notified if experiments were classified.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The Soviet nuclear program also included medical study of exposed citizens living near Semipalatinsk Test Site, withholding information about nuclear testing or health risks.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The program also involved severe radiation exposures to workers of the Mayak facility, especially the early work of forced laborers on the A-1 nuclear reactor.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Criminal activity has involved murder and attempted murder carried out through abrupt victim contact with a radioactive substance such as polonium or plutonium.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The death of Alexander Litvinenko is widely believed to be assassination via polonium poisoning and on the order of the Russian FSB, and polonium is also suspected as the cause of death for Yasser Arafat, Yuri Shchekochikhin, Lecha Islamov and Roman Tsepov.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The most commonly used predictor of ARS is the whole-body absorbed dose.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Several related quantities, such as the equivalent dose, effective dose, and committed dose, are used to gauge long-term stochastic biological effects such as cancer incidence, but they are not designed to evaluate ARS.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] To help avoid confusion between these quantities, absorbed dose is measured in units of grays (in SI, unit symbol *Gy*) or rad (in CGS), while the others are measured in sieverts (in SI, unit symbol *Sv*) or rem (in CGS).
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] In most of the acute exposure scenarios that lead to radiation sickness, the bulk of the radiation is external whole-body gamma, in which case the absorbed, equivalent, and effective doses are all equal.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] There are exceptions, such as the Therac-25 accidents and the 1958 Cecil Kelley criticality accident, where the absorbed doses in Gy or rad are the only useful quantities, because of the targeted nature of the exposure to the body.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Radiotherapy treatments are typically prescribed in terms of the local absorbed dose, which might be 60 Gy or higher.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The dose is fractionated to about 2 Gy per day for *curative* treatment, which allows normal tissues to undergo repair, allowing them to tolerate a higher dose than would otherwise be expected.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The dose to the targeted tissue mass must be averaged over the entire body mass, most of which receives negligible radiation, to arrive at a whole-body absorbed dose that can be compared to the table above.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Exposure to high doses of radiation causes DNA damage, later creating serious and even lethal chromosomal aberrations if left unrepaired.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Ionizing radiation can produce reactive oxygen species, and does directly damage cells by causing localized ionization events.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The former is very damaging to DNA, while the latter events create clusters of DNA damage.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] This damage includes loss of nucleobases and breakage of the sugar-phosphate backbone that binds to the nucleobases.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The DNA organization at the level of histones, nucleosomes, and chromatin also affects its susceptibility to radiation damage.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Clustered damage, defined as at least two lesions within a helical turn, is especially harmful.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] While DNA damage happens frequently and naturally in the cell from endogenous sources, clustered damage is a unique effect of radiation exposure.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Clustered damage takes longer to repair than isolated breakages, and is less likely to be repaired at all.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Larger radiation doses are more prone to cause tighter clustering of damage, and closely localized damage is increasingly less likely to be repaired.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Somatic mutations cannot be passed down from parent to offspring, but these mutations can propagate in cell lines within an organism.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Radiation damage can also cause chromosome and chromatid aberrations, and their effects depend on in which stage of the mitotic cycle the cell is when the irradiation occurs.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] If the cell is in interphase, while it is still a single strand of chromatin, the damage will be replicated during the S1 phase of the cell cycle, and there will be a break on both chromosome arms; the damage then will be apparent in both daughter cells.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] If the irradiation occurs after replication, only one arm will bear the damage; this damage will be apparent in only one daughter cell.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] A damaged chromosome may cyclize, binding to another chromosome, or to itself.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Diagnosis is typically made based on a history of significant radiation exposure and suitable clinical findings.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] An absolute lymphocyte count can give a rough estimate of radiation exposure.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Time from exposure to vomiting can also give estimates of exposure levels if they are less than 10 Gy (1000 rad).
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] A guiding principle of radiation safety is *as low as reasonably achievable* (ALARA).
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] This means try to avoid exposure as much as possible and includes the three components of time, distance, and shielding.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The longer that humans are subjected to radiation the larger the dose will be.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The advice in the nuclear war manual entitled *Nuclear War Survival Skills* published by Cresson Kearny in the U.S. was that if one needed to leave the shelter then this should be done as rapidly as possible to minimize exposure.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] In chapter 12, he states that "[q]uickly putting or dumping wastes outside is not hazardous once fallout is no longer being deposited.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] For example, assume the shelter is in an area of heavy fallout and the dose rate outside is 400 roentgen (R) per hour, enough to give a potentially fatal dose in about an hour to a person exposed in the open.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] If a person needs to be exposed for only 10 seconds to dump a bucket, in this 1/360 of an hour he will receive a dose of only about 1 R.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Under war conditions, an additional 1-R dose is of little concern." In peacetime, radiation workers are taught to work as quickly as possible when performing a task that exposes them to radiation, such as for instance during recovery of a radioactive source.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Usually, matter attenuates radiation, so placing any mass (for instance, lead, dirt, sandbags, vehicles, water, even air) between humans and the source will reduce the radiation dose.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] This is not always the case, however; care should be taken when constructing shielding for a specific purpose.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] For example, although high atomic number materials are very effective in shielding photons, using them to shield beta particles may cause higher radiation exposure due to the production of bremsstrahlung x-rays, and hence low atomic number materials are recommended.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Also, using material with a high neutron activation cross section to shield neutrons will result in the shielding material itself becoming radioactive and hence more dangerous than if it were not present.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] There are many types of shielding strategies that can be used to reduce the effects of radiation exposure.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Internal contamination protective equipment such as respirators are used to prevent internal deposition as a result of inhalation and ingestion of radioactive material.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Dermal protective equipment, which protects against external contamination, provides shielding to prevent radioactive material from being deposited on external structures.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] While these protective measures do provide a barrier from radioactive material deposition, they do not shield from externally penetrating gamma radiation.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] This leaves anyone exposed to penetrating gamma rays at high risk of ARS.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Naturally, shielding the entire body from high energy gamma radiation is optimal, but the required mass to provide adequate attenuation makes functional movement nearly impossible.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] In the event of a radiation catastrophe, medical and security personnel need mobile protection equipment in order to safely assist in containment, evacuation, and many other necessary public safety objectives.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Research has been done exploring the feasibility of partial body shielding, a radiation protection strategy that provides adequate attenuation to only the most radio-sensitive organs and tissues inside the body.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Irreversible stem cell damage in the bone marrow is the first life-threatening effect of intense radiation exposure and therefore one of the most important bodily elements to protect.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Due to the regenerative property of hematopoietic stem cells, it is only necessary to protect enough bone marrow to repopulate the exposed areas of the body with the shielded supply.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] This concept allows for the development of lightweight mobile radiation protection equipment, which provides adequate protection, deferring the onset of ARS to much higher exposure doses.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] One example of such equipment is the 360 Gamma, a radiation protection belt that applies selective shielding to protect the bone marrow stored in the pelvic area as well as other radio sensitive organs in the abdominal region without hindering functional mobility.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Where radioactive contamination is present, an elastomeric respirator, dust mask, or good hygiene practices may offer protection, depending on the nature of the contaminant.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Potassium iodide (KI) tablets can reduce the risk of cancer in some situations due to slower uptake of ambient radioiodine.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Although this does not protect any organ other than the thyroid gland, their effectiveness is still highly dependent on the time of ingestion, which would protect the gland for the duration of a twenty-four-hour period.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] They do not prevent ARS as they provide no shielding from other environmental radionuclides.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] If an intentional dose is broken up into a number of smaller doses, with time allowed for recovery between irradiations, the same total dose causes less cell death.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Even without interruptions, a reduction in dose rate below 0.1 Gy/h also tends to reduce cell death.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] This technique is routinely used in radiotherapy.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The human body contains many types of cells and a human can be killed by the loss of a single type of cells in a vital organ.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] For many short term radiation deaths (3–30 days), the loss of two important types of cells that are constantly being regenerated causes death.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The loss of cells forming blood cells (bone marrow) and the cells in the digestive system (microvilli, which form part of the wall of the intestines) is fatal.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Treatment usually involves supportive care with possible symptomatic measures employed.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The former involves the possible use of antibiotics, blood products, colony stimulating factors, and stem cell transplant.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] There is a direct relationship between the degree of the neutropenia that emerges after exposure to radiation and the increased risk of developing infection.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Since there are no controlled studies of therapeutic intervention in humans, most of the current recommendations are based on animal research.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The treatment of established or suspected infection following exposure to radiation (characterized by neutropenia and fever) is similar to the one used for other febrile neutropenic patients.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] However, important differences between the two conditions exist.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Individuals that develop neutropenia after exposure to radiation are also susceptible to irradiation damage in other tissues, such as the gastrointestinal tract, lungs and central nervous system.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] These patients may require therapeutic interventions not needed in other types of neutropenic patients.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The response of irradiated animals to antimicrobial therapy can be unpredictable, as was evident in experimental studies where metronidazole and pefloxacin therapies were detrimental.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Antimicrobials that reduce the number of the strict anaerobic component of the gut flora (for instance, metronidazole) generally should not be given because they may enhance systemic infection by aerobic or facultative bacteria, thus facilitating mortality after irradiation.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] An empirical regimen of antimicrobials should be chosen based on the pattern of bacterial susceptibility and nosocomial infections in the affected area and medical center and the degree of neutropenia.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Broad-spectrum empirical therapy (see below for choices) with high doses of one or more antibiotics should be initiated at the onset of fever.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] These antimicrobials should be directed at the eradication of Gram-negative aerobic bacilli (that is, Enterobacteriaceae, *Pseudomonas*), which account for more than three quarters of the isolates causing sepsis.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Because aerobic and facultative Gram-positive bacteria (mostly alpha-hemolytic streptococci) cause sepsis in about a quarter of the victims, coverage for these organisms may also be needed.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] A standardized management plan for people with neutropenia and fever should be devised.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The prognosis for ARS is dependent on the exposure dose, with anything above 8 Gy being almost always lethal, even with medical care.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Radiation burns from lower-level exposures usually manifest after 2 months, while reactions from the burns occur months to years after radiation treatment.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Complications from ARS include an increased risk of developing radiation-induced cancer later in life.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] According to the controversial but commonly applied linear no-threshold model, any exposure to ionizing radiation, even at doses too low to produce any symptoms of radiation sickness, can induce cancer due to cellular and genetic damage.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The probability of developing cancer is a linear function with respect to the effective radiation dose.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Radiation cancer may occur after ionizing radiation exposure following a latent period averaging 20 to 40 years.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Acute effects of ionizing radiation were first observed when Wilhelm Röntgen intentionally subjected his fingers to X-rays in 1895.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] He published his observations concerning the burns that developed that eventually healed, and misattributed them to ozone.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Röntgen believed the free radical produced in air by X-rays from the ozone was the cause, but other free radicals produced within the body are now understood to be more important.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] David Walsh first established the symptoms of radiation sickness in 1897.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Ingestion of radioactive materials caused many radiation-induced cancers in the 1930s, but no one was exposed to high enough doses at high enough rates to bring on ARS.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki resulted in high acute doses of radiation to a large number of Japanese people, allowing for greater insight into its symptoms and dangers.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Red Cross Hospital Surgeon Terufumi Sasaki led intensive research into the syndrome in the weeks and months following the Hiroshima and Nagasaki bombings.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Sasaki and his team were able to monitor the effects of radiation in patients of varying proximities to the blast itself, leading to the establishment of three recorded stages of the syndrome.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Within 25–30 days of the explosion, Sasaki noticed a sharp drop in white blood cell count and established this drop, along with symptoms of fever, as prognostic standards for ARS.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Actress Midori Naka, who was present during the atomic bombing of Hiroshima, was the first incident of radiation poisoning to be extensively studied.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Her death on 24 August 1945 was the first death ever to be officially certified as a result of ARS (or "Atomic bomb disease").
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] There are two major databases that track radiation accidents: The American ORISE REAC/TS and the European IRSN ACCIRAD.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] REAC/TS shows 417 accidents occurring between 1944 and 2000, causing about 3000 cases of ARS, of which 127 were fatal.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] ACCIRAD lists 580 accidents with 180 ARS fatalities for an almost identical period.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The two deliberate bombings are not included in either database, nor are any possible radiation-induced cancers from low doses.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The detailed accounting is difficult because of confounding factors.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] ARS may be accompanied by conventional injuries such as steam burns, or may occur in someone with a pre-existing condition undergoing radiotherapy.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] There may be multiple causes for death, and the contribution from radiation may be unclear.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Some documents may incorrectly refer to radiation-induced cancers as radiation poisoning, or may count all overexposed individuals as survivors without mentioning if they had any symptoms of ARS.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The following table includes only individuals known to have symptoms of ARS.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Excluded are cases of chronic radiation syndrome, such as the case of Albert Stevens.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Chronic radiation syndrome is characterized by an exposure of lower doses of radiation, over a longer duration, than with ARS.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The table also excludes cases where an individual was exposed to so much radiation that death occurred before medical assistance or dose estimations could be made, such as an attempted cobalt-60 thief who reportedly died 30 minutes after exposure.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] The result column represents the time from exposure to the time of death.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] As ARS is measured by a whole-body absorbed dose, the exposure column only includes units of gray (Gy).
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] Thousands of scientific experiments have been performed to study ARS in animals.
[src:air-quality-index/acute-radiation-syndrome] There is a simple guide for predicting survival and death in mammals, including humans, following the acute effects of inhaling radioactive particles.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] The achievement of these objectives requires an open management process which seeks to include past, present and future stakeholders.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Adaptive management needs to at least maintain political openness, but usually aims to create it.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Adaptive management must therefore be a scientific and social process.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] It must focus on the development of new institutions and institutional strategies in balance with scientific hypothesis and experimental frameworks (resilience.org).
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Adaptive management can proceed as either passive or active adaptive management, depending on how learning takes place.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Passive adaptive management values learning only insofar as it improves decision outcomes (i.e. passively), as measured by the specified utility function.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] In contrast, active adaptive management explicitly incorporates learning as part of the objective function, and hence, decisions which improve learning are valued over those which do not.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] In both cases, as new knowledge is gained, the models are updated and optimal management strategies are derived accordingly.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Thus, while learning occurs in both cases, it is treated differently.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Often, deriving actively adaptive policies is technically very difficult, which prevents it being more commonly applied.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] The use of adaptive management techniques can be traced back to peoples from ancient civilisations.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] For example, the Yap people of Micronesia have been using adaptive management techniques to sustain high population densities in the face of resource scarcity for thousands of years (Falanruw 1984).
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] In using these techniques, the Yap people have altered their environment creating, for example, coastal mangrove depressions and seagrass meadows to support fishing and termite resistant wood (Stankey and Shinder 1997).
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] The origin of the adaptive management concept can be traced back to ideas of scientific management pioneered by Frederick Taylor in the early 1900s (Haber 1964).
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] While the term "adaptive management" evolved in natural resource management workshops through decision makers, managers and scientists focussing on building simulation models to uncover key assumptions and uncertainties.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Two ecologists at The University of British Columbia, C.S.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Holling and C.J Walters further developed the adaptive management approach as they distinguished between passive and active adaptive management practice.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Kai Lee, notable Princeton physicist, expanded upon the approach in the late 1970s and early 1980s while pursuing a post-doctorate degree at UC Berkeley.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] The approach was further developed at the International Institute for Applied Systems Analysis (IIASA) in Vienna, Austria, while C.S.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] In 1992, Hilbourne described three learning models for federal land managers, around which adaptive management approaches could be developed, these are reactive, passive and active.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Adaptive management has probably been most frequently applied in Yap, Australia and North America, initially applied in fishery management, but received more broad application in the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] One of the most successful applications of adaptive management has been in the area of waterfowl harvest management in North America, most notably for the mallard.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Adaptive management in a conservation project and program context can trace its roots back to at least the early 1990s, with the establishment of the Biodiversity Support Program (BSP) in 1989.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] BSP was a USAID-funded consortium of WWF, The Nature Conservancy (TNC), and World Resources Institute (WRI).
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Its Analysis and Adaptive Management Program sought to understand the conditions under which certain conservation strategies were most effective and to identify lessons learned across conservation projects.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] When BSP ended in 2001, TNC and Foundations of Success (FOS, a non-profit which grew out of BSP) continued to actively work in promoting adaptive management for conservation projects and programs.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] The approaches used included Conservation by Design (TNC) and Measures of Success (FOS).
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] In 2004, the Conservation Measures Partnership (CMP) – which includes several former BSP members – developed a common set of standards and guidelines for applying adaptive management to conservation projects and programs.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Applying adaptive management in a conservation or ecosystem management project involves the integration of project/program design, management, and monitoring to systematically test assumptions in order to adapt and learn.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] The concept of adaptive management is not restricted to natural resources or ecosystem management, as similar concepts have been applied to international development programming.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] This has often been a recognition to the "wicked" nature of many development challenges and the limits of traditional planning processes.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] One of the principal changes facing international development organizations is the need to be more flexible, adaptable and focused on learning.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] This is reflected in international development approaches such as Doing Development Differently, Politically Informed Programming and Problem Driven Iterative Adaptation.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] One recent example of the use of adaptive management by international development donors is the planned Global Learning for Adaptive Management (GLAM) programme to support adaptive management in Department for International Development and USAID.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] The program is establishing a centre for learning about adaptive management to support the utilization and accessibility of adaptive management.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] In addition, donors have been focused on amending their own programmatic guidance to reflect the importance of learning within programs: for instance, USAID's recent focus in their ADS guidance on the importance of collaborating, learning and adapting.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] This is also reflected in Department for International Development's Smart Rules that provide the operating framework for their programs including the use of evidence to inform their decisions.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] There are a variety of tools used to operationalize adaptive management in programs, such as learning agendas and decision cycles.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Collaborating, learning and adapting (CLA) is a concept related to the operationalizing of adaptive management in international development that describes a specific way of designing, implementing, adapting and evaluating programs.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] 3. adapting strategically based on applied learning.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] CLA practices have tangible benefits; for instance, a recent study recently found that companies "which apply more data-driven and adaptive leadership practices perform better" when examined against those which focus less on those practices.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] CLA integrates three closely connected concepts within the organizational theory literature: namely collaborating, learning and adapting.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] There is evidence of the benefits of collaborating internally within an organization and externally with organizations.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Much of the production and transmission of knowledge—both explicit knowledge and tacit knowledge—occurs through collaboration.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] There is evidence for the importance of collaboration among individuals and groups for innovation, knowledge production, and diffusion—for example, the benefits of staff interacting with one another and transmitting knowledge.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] The importance of collaboration is closely linked to the ability of organizations to collectively learn from each other, a concept noted in the literature on learning organizations.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] CLA has been linked to a part of USAID's commitment to becoming a learning organization.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] CLA represents an approach to combine strategic collaboration, continuous learning, and adaptive management.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] A part of integrating the CLA approach is providing tools and resources, such as the Learning Lab, to staff and partner organizations.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] The CLA approach is detailed for USAID staff in the recently revised program policy guidance.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Adaptive management as a systematic process for improving environmental management policies and practices is the traditional application however, the adaptive management framework can also be applied to other sectors seeking sustainability solutions such as business and community development.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Adaptive management as a strategy emphasizes the need to change with the environment and to learn from doing.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Adaptive management applied to ecosystems makes overt sense when considering ever changing environmental conditions.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] The flexibility and constant learning of an adaptive management approach is also a logical application for organizations seeking sustainability methodologies.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Businesses pursuing sustainability strategies would employ an adaptive management framework to ensure that the organization is prepared for the unexpected and geared for change.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] By applying an adaptive management approach the business begins to function as an integrated system adjusting and learning from a multi-faceted network of influences not just environmental but also, economic and social (Dunphy, Griffths, & Benn, 2007).
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] The goal of any sustainable organization guided by adaptive management principals must be to engage in active learning to direct change towards sustainability (Verine, 2008).
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] This "learning to manage by managing to learn" (Bormann BT, 1993) will be at the core of a sustainable business strategy.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Sustainable community development requires recognition of the relationship between environment, economics and social instruments within the community.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] An adaptive management approach to creating sustainable community policy and practice also emphasizes the connection and confluence of those elements.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] A practical example of adaptive management as a tool for sustainability was the application of a modified variation of adaptive management using artvoice, photovoice, and agent-based modeling in a participatory social framework of action.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] This application was used in field research on tribal lands to first identify the environmental issue and impact of illegal trash dumping and then to discover a solution through iterative agent-based modeling using NetLogo on a theoretical "regional cooperative clean-energy economy".
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] This cooperative economy incorporated a mixed application of: traditional trash recycling and a waste-to-fuels process of carbon recycling of non-recyclable trash into ethanol fuel.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] This industrial waste-to-fuels application was inspired by pioneering work of the Canadian-based company, Enerkem.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] See Bruss, 2012 - PhD dissertation: Human Environment Interactions and Collaborative Adaptive Capacity Building in a Resilience Framework, GDPE Colorado State University.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] It is difficult to test the effectiveness of adaptive management in comparison to other management approaches.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] One challenge is that once a system is managed using one approach it is difficult to determine how another approach would have performed in exactly the same situation.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] One study tested the effectiveness of formal passive adaptive management in comparison to human intuition by having natural resource management students make decisions about how to harvest a hypothetical fish population in an online computer game.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] The students on average performed poorly in comparison to the computer programs implementing passive adaptive management.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Collaborative adaptive management is often celebrated as an effective way to deal with natural resource management under high levels of conflict, uncertainty and complexity.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] The effectiveness of these efforts can be constrained by both social and technical barriers.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] In Colorado, USA, a ten-year, ranch-scale (2590 ha) experiment began in 2012 at the Agricultural Research Service (ARS) Central Plains Experimental range to evaluate the effectiveness and process of collaborative adaptive management on rangelands.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] The Collaborative Adaptive Rangeland Management or “CARM” project monitors outcomes from yearling steer grazing management on 10, 130 ha pastures conducted by a group of conservationists, ranchers, and public employees, and researchers.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] This team compares ecological monitoring data tracking profitability and conservation outcomes with outcomes from a “traditional” management treatment: a second set of ten pastures managed without adaptive decision making but with the same stocking rate.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Early evaluations of the project by social scientists offer insights for more effective adaptive management.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] First, trust is primary and essential to learning in adaptive management, not a side benefit.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Second, practitioners cannot assume that extensive monitoring data or large-scale efforts will automatically facilitate successful collaborative adaptive management.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Active, long-term efforts to build trust among scientists and stakeholders are also important.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Finally, explicit efforts to understand, share and respect multiple types of manager knowledge, including place-based ecological knowledge practiced by local managers, is necessary to manage adaptively for multiple conservation and livelihood goals on rangelands.
[src:air-quality-index/adaptive-management] Practitioners can expect adaptive management to be a complex, non-linear process shaped by social, political and ecological processes, as well as by data collection and interpretation.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Advertising mail includes advertising circulars, plastic mailers, coupon envelopes (Money Mailer, Valpak), catalogs, CDs, "pre-approved" credit card applications, and other commercial merchandising materials delivered to homes and businesses.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] It may be addressed to pre-selected individuals, or unaddressed and delivered on a neighbourhood-by-neighbourhood basis.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] North Carolina state historians say Lunsford Richardson "is widely to considered to have invented ‘junk mail.’" In the process of expanding the market for his new products made by the Vicks company of Greensboro, North Carolina.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Postal Service began allowing mail to be sent to rural addresses without including the name of the addressee.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Vicks sent out millions of samples of Vicks VapoRub.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Postal systems offer lower rates for buyers of bulk mail permits.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] In order to qualify for these rates, marketers must format and sort the mail in specific ways – which reduces the handling required by the postal service.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Income from advertising mail represents a significant and growing portion of some postal services' budgets, and it is a service actively marketed by them.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] In the United States, ad mail dollars decreased from $96.6 billion in 2004, to $80.9 billion in 2013.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] A study by Boston Consulting Group predicts that overall share of ad-spend in the US will increase from 11% in to 12% by 2020.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] In Canada, addressed and unaddressed advertising mail accounted for 20% of Canada Post's revenue in 2005, and the share is increasing.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Postal services employ the terms *advertising mail*, *admail*, and *direct mail*, while avoiding and objecting to the pejorative term *junk mail*.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] The United States Postal Service offers a direct mail service known as Every Door Direct Mail, that provides resources allowing businesses to target, design, print and mail to specific households without needing to know the addresses.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] In many developed countries, advertising mail represents a significant and growing amount of the total volume of mail.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] In the United States, "Standard mail: advertising" comprised 29% of all mail in 1980 and 43% in 2003.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Direct mail is a common form of direct marketing, and may be employed by for-profit businesses, charities and other non-profits, political campaigns, and other organizations.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Direct mail encompasses a wide variety of marketing materials, including brochures, catalogs, postcards, newsletters and sales letters.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] In 2015 more than 150 million direct mail promotions were sent out with a reported 42% of respondents scanning or reading the mail.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Scammers also use direct mail in the form of auto warranty and home warranty scams.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Copywriters write the words, also known as copy, for direct mail.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] These copywriters are known inside the trade as direct response copywriters.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Direct response copy follows a proven format based on testing results.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Graphic designers who specialize in direct marketing also play a key role in the success of direct mail programs.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Many direct mail marketers will mail different version of copy (A/B testing) to test the effectiveness of different appeals.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] The winning mail package will be known as the control and the direct mail company will continue to mail the control until a different package produces improved results, usually measured by metrics such as revenue and conversion rate.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Some campaigns incorporate tactile embellishments—such as foil stamping, embossing, specialty UV coatings, metallic finishes, and soft-touch laminates—to attract attention and encourage interaction.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Advertisers often refine direct mail practices into targeted mailing in which mail is sent following database analysis to select recipients considered most likely to respond positively.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] This reduces costs for mailers by narrowing the mailing universe to only the most likely audience.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] For example, a person who has demonstrated an interest in golf may receive direct mail for golf-related products or perhaps for goods and services that are appropriate for golfers.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] This use of database analysis is a type of database marketing.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Alternatively, unaddressed direct mail may be sent on a neighbourhood-by-neighbourhood basis.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Whether at the individual or neighbourhood level, direct mail marketing allows recipients to be targeted, attempting to match the demographic profile of the recipients to one most closely matching that of likely customers.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Individually targeted direct mail may be tailored based on previous transactions and gathered data.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] For example, all male recipients of an offer may receive a personalized package with a man's picture on the cover while all female recipients receive a picture of a woman.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Often advertisers will include a Johnson Box in letters.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] These are aimed at drawing the targeted consumers into reading further in the letter.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] To the non-professional, direct mail may seem wasteful, yet the medium can be one of the most cost-effective.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Database targeting combined with an effective pricing, creative and list strategy can reduce waste and maximize profitable results for the mailer.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Testing is accomplished in a variety of ways including A/B split testing of new mailings versus a control and testing lists through "Nth" name selects.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Political campaigns make frequent use of direct mail, both to gain votes from the electorate as a whole, and to target certain groups of voters thought to be open to a candidate's message and to appeal for campaign funds.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Certain organizations and individuals have become known for their prowess in direct mail, including in the US, the Free Congress Foundation in the 1970s, Response Dynamics, Inc. in the 1980s, the National Congressional Club, and Richard Viguerie.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] With the advent of the Internet in political campaigns, direct mail became just one of many campaign management tools, but still played a significant role.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Nonprofit companies use direct mail marketing as a consistent form of advertising.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] In its modern form, direct mail fundraising appeared in the United States after World War II when nationwide charities such as the National Easter Seal Society sought ways to broaden their fundraising base.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] It was only with the advent in the 1960s of the ZIP code and, later, the computer that direct mail fundraising began to gain wide use.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Before the ZIP code, it was difficult to target appropriate recipients of direct mail fundraising appeals, and before the computer, compiling and maintaining lists of supporters was tedious and costly.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] During the 1970s, when computers became increasingly affordable, the use of direct mail fundraising spread widely.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] It quickly became the means by which most Americans learned about and first provided financial support for their charities of choice.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] The explosive growth of the nonprofit sector in the United States—quadrupling in the 1980s and doubling again in the 1990s and early 2000s—led to a massive expansion in the use of direct mail to build and sustain large, nationwide donor and membership lists.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] In recent years, electronic communication media has been used more commonly among nonprofits.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Online, email, and social media campaigns, collectively referred to as digital fundraising, have been used in coordination with direct mail fundraising.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Nonprofits supplement direct mail campaigns with email blasts and social media posts, using similar messaging and visuals to tie the various communications together.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] However, digital fundraising has not grown fast enough to replace direct mail for most nonprofits.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] In 2012, digital fundraising accounted for 7 percent of charitable donations in the United States.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] This form of marketing is increasingly used by charitable groups in the UK.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] In 2013, £239 million was spent by British charities on direct mail advertising campaigns.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Direct mail marketing is under scrutiny by many of its former and current advocates.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] The arguments against using direct mail marketing include possible impact on the environment and changing attitudes among consumers.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] In the United States, the common practice of address standardization can defeat the purpose of advertising mail by stripping away local identity, thus leaving many recipients alienated.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] It is also argued that direct mail is not cost-efficient.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] It has been suggested that social media will eventually replace direct mail as the preferred method for marketing communications.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Those who believe direct mail marketing has a future cite its strong growth in 2011.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] It has been reported that large publishers like the Tribune Company and RR Donnelley have growing direct mail divisions.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Nonprofit organizations continue to use direct mail at a subsidized USPS rate.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] When targeted to other businesses rather than individuals, direct mail is known as a business-to-business mailing.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Traditionally, this worked in one of two ways: as a direct sale, therefore precluding the use of a salesperson or a retail store, or as a method of generating leads for a salesforce.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] The former method was ideally used by products that were easy to sell, were familiar to the prospect and needed no demonstration.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] The latter method was used for large-ticket items or for those that needed demonstration, for example.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] One method of direct mailing used in B2B is known as "bill-me." In this direct-mail marketing offer, the buyer is shipped the product prior to payment and is then sent an invoice later.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Several organizations offer opt-out services to people who wish to reduce or eliminate the amount of addressed advertising mail they receive.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] In the UK, the Mailing Preference Service allows people to register with them for removal from posted as opposed to hand-delivered mail.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] As of 2017 in the United States two organizations offering these services include Catalog Choice and DMAChoice.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] A similar organization by the name of 41pounds.org received customer complaints and then became defunct.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Another one by the name of Tonic Mailstopper (formerly GreenDimes) no longer appears to be in business either.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Several websites critical of junk mail have guides for people interested in reducing the amount of junk mail they get, such as the Center for a New American Dream.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] In response to a US Supreme Court ruling (*Rowan v.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] 728 (1970)), the United States Postal Service enables an applicant to obtain a Prohibitory Order, which gives people the power to stop non-governmental organizations from sending them mail, and to demand such organizations remove the consumers’ information from their mailing lists.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] In Canada, the highly publicized Red Dot Campaign offers advice on reducing unaddressed advertising mail.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] The campaign focuses on advertising the Canada Post policy to respect "No Junkmail" signs, noting that this policy is not promoted by Canada Post itself.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] The name "red dot" refers to an internal marker used by Canada Post to indicate which households do not wish to receive unaddressed admail.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] The UK Royal Mail also offers an opt-out service, though unaddressed government mailings cannot be separated from advertisements, and those who opted out of the latter would stop receiving the former as well.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Several environmental groups express concern about the environmental impact generated by direct mail.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] In the US, the Environmental Protection Agency estimates that 44% of junk mail is discarded without being opened or read, equalling four million tons of waste paper per year, with 32% recovered for recycling.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Further, the Ohio Office of Compliance Assistance and Pollution Prevention (OCAPP) estimates that 250,000 homes could be heated for a single day's junk mail (70,000,000,000,000/3 btus of energy or 28,870,000,000/21 kWh of energy).
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] In the UK, the Minister of State responsible for the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs estimated that "direct mail and promotions" accounted for between 500,000 and 600,000 tonnes of paper in 2002, with 13% being recycled.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] The government and the Direct Marketing Association (UK) together agreed on recycling targets for the direct mail industry, including a goal of 55% by 2009, though the DMA's latest estimates are that the industry will fall well short of this mark.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Mike Berners-Lee estimates that receiving five letters per day plus two printed catalogs per week results in 480 kilograms (1,060 lb) CO2e per year.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] A *New York Times* article from 2009 states that in the United States 51.5 million metric tons of greenhouse gases are emitted each year from mail advertisements.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] The Environmental Protection Agency indicates that in 2009 total US greenhouse gas emissions were 6,700.10 million metric tons.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Recipients may conceive of advertising mail as a privacy problem, both because its generation requires extensive collection and use of information, and because receipt of mail can be an intrusion into the home.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Researchers at the University of California recently found that four out of five Americans favor a do-not-mail law, similar to the existing do-not-call telemarketing registry.
[src:air-quality-index/advertising-mail] Advertising mail has been criticized as a form of attention theft.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] An **aerosol** is a suspension of fine solid particles or liquid droplets in air or another gas.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Aerosols can be generated from natural or human causes.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The scientific term *aerosol* refers to the mixture of particulates in gas, and not to the particulate matter alone.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The liquid or solid particles in an aerosol have diameters typically less than 1 μm.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Larger particles with a significant settling speed make the mixture a suspension, although the distinction is not clear.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Examples of natural aerosols are fog, mist, and dust from geological or biological sources.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Certain infections spread by means of small droplets in the breath, sometimes called bioaerosols.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Several types of atmospheric aerosol have a significant effect on Earth's climate: volcanic, desert dust, sea-salt, originating from biogenic sources and human-made.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Volcanic aerosol forms in the stratosphere after an eruption as droplets of sulfuric acid that can prevail for up to two years, and reflect sunlight, lowering temperature.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Desert dust, mineral particles blown to high altitudes, absorb heat and may be responsible for inhibiting storm cloud formation.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] In everyday language, *aerosol* often refers to a dispensing system that delivers a consumer product from a spray can.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Other examples of human caused aerosols include perfume from atomizers, medical treatments for respiratory illnesses, dust from material or industrial sources, smoke, irrigation mist, sprayed pesticides, particulate air pollutants, and mist from the discharge at hydroelectric dams.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Human-made sulfate aerosols, primarily from burning oil and coal, affect the behavior of clouds.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] When aerosols absorb pollutants, it facilitates the deposition of pollutants to the surface of the earth as well as to bodies of water.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] This has the potential to be damaging to both the environment and human health.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Ship tracks are clouds that form around the exhaust released by ships into the still ocean air.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Water molecules collect around the tiny particles (aerosols) from exhaust to form a cloud seed.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] More and more water accumulates on the seed until a visible cloud is formed.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] In the case of ship tracks, the cloud seeds are stretched over a long narrow path where the wind has blown the ship's exhaust, so the resulting clouds resemble long strings over the ocean.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The warming caused by human-produced greenhouse gases has been somewhat offset by the cooling effect of human-produced aerosols.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] In 2020, regulations on fuel significantly cut sulfur dioxide emissions from international shipping by approximately 80%, leading to an unexpected global geoengineering termination shock.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Aerosol is defined as a suspension system of solid or liquid particles in a gas.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] An aerosol includes both the particles and the suspending gas, which is usually air.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Meteorologists and climatologists often refer to them as particle matter, while the classification in sizes ranges like PM2.5 or PM10, is useful in the field of atmospheric pollution as these size range play a role in ascertain the harmful effects in human health.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Donnan presumably first used the term *aerosol* during World War I to describe an aero-solution, clouds of microscopic particles in air.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] This term developed analogously to the term hydrosol, a colloid system with water as the dispersed medium.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] *Primary aerosols* contain particles introduced directly into the gas; *secondary aerosols* form through gas-to-particle conversion.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Key aerosol groups include sulfates, organic carbon, black carbon, nitrates, mineral dust, and sea salt, they usually clump together to form a complex mixture.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Various types of aerosol, classified according to physical form and how they were generated, include dust, fume, mist, smoke and fog.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] There are several measures of aerosol concentration.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Environmental science and environmental health often use the *mass concentration* (*M*), defined as the mass of particulate matter per unit volume, in units such as μg/m3.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Also commonly used is the *number concentration* (*N*), the number of particles per unit volume, in units such as number per m3 or number per cm3.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Particle size has a major influence on particle properties, and the aerosol particle radius or diameter (*dp*) is a key property used to characterise aerosols.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] A *monodisperse* aerosol, producible in the laboratory, contains particles of uniform size.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Most aerosols, however, as *polydisperse* colloidal systems, exhibit a range of particle sizes.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Liquid droplets are almost always nearly spherical, but scientists use an *equivalent diameter* to characterize the properties of various shapes of solid particles, some very irregular.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The equivalent diameter is the diameter of a spherical particle with the same value of some physical property as the irregular particle.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The *equivalent volume diameter* (*de*) is defined as the diameter of a sphere of the same volume as that of the irregular particle.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Also commonly used is the aerodynamic diameter, *da*.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Several types of atmospheric aerosol have a significant effect on Earth's climate: volcanic, desert dust, sea-salt, that originating from biogenic sources and human-made.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Although all hydrometeors, solid and liquid, can be described as aerosols, a distinction is commonly made between such dispersions (i.e. clouds and precipitation) containing relatively large water drops or ice crystals, and aerosol particles.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The presence of aerosols in the Earth's atmosphere can influence its climate, as well as human health.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Volcanic eruptions release large amounts of sulphuric acid, hydrogen sulfide and hydrochloric acid into the atmosphere.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] These gases represent aerosols and eventually return to earth as acid rain, having a number of adverse effects on the environment and human life.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Aerosols interact with the Earth's energy budget in two ways, directly and indirectly.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Aerosol particles with an effective diameter smaller than 10 μm can enter the bronchi, while the ones with an effective diameter smaller than 2.5 μm can enter as far as the gas exchange region in the lungs, which can be hazardous to human health.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] For a monodisperse aerosol, a single number—the particle diameter—suffices to describe the size of the particles.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] However, more complicated particle-size distributions describe the sizes of the particles in a polydisperse aerosol.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] This distribution defines the relative amounts of particles, sorted according to size.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] One approach to defining the particle size distribution uses a list of the sizes of every particle in a sample.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] However, this approach proves tedious to ascertain in aerosols with millions of particles and awkward to use.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Another approach splits the size range into intervals and finds the number (or proportion) of particles in each interval.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The particle size distribution can be approximated.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The normal distribution usually does not suitably describe particle size distributions in aerosols because of the skewness associated with a long tail of larger particles.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Also for a quantity that varies over a large range, as many aerosol sizes do, the width of the distribution implies negative particles sizes, which is not physically realistic.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] However, the normal distribution can be suitable for some aerosols, such as test aerosols, certain pollen grains and spores.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The log-normal distribution has no negative values, can cover a wide range of values, and fits many observed size distributions reasonably well.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] For low values of the Reynolds number (<1), true for most aerosol motion, Stokes' law describes the force of resistance on a solid spherical particle in a fluid.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] However, Stokes' law is only valid when the velocity of the gas at the surface of the particle is zero.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] For small particles (< 1 μm) that characterize aerosols, however, this assumption fails.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] To account for this failure, one can introduce the Cunningham correction factor, always greater than 1.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] This allows us to calculate the terminal velocity of a particle undergoing gravitational settling in still air.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] is the terminal settling velocity of the particle.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The terminal velocity can also be derived for other kinds of forces.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] If Stokes' law holds, then the resistance to motion is directly proportional to speed.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] To account for the effect of the shape of non-spherical particles, a correction factor known as the *dynamic shape factor* is applied to Stokes' law.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The aerodynamic diameter of an irregular particle is defined as the diameter of the spherical particle with a density of 1000 kg/m3 and the same settling velocity as the irregular particle.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] One can apply the aerodynamic diameter to particulate pollutants or to inhaled drugs to predict where in the respiratory tract such particles deposit.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Pharmaceutical companies typically use aerodynamic diameter, not geometric diameter, to characterize particles in inhalable drugs.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The previous discussion focused on single aerosol particles.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] In contrast, *aerosol dynamics* explains the evolution of complete aerosol populations.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The concentrations of particles will change over time as a result of many processes.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] External processes that move particles outside a volume of gas under study include diffusion, gravitational settling, and electric charges and other external forces that cause particle migration.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] A second set of processes internal to a given volume of gas include particle formation (nucleation), evaporation, chemical reaction, and coagulation.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] A differential equation called the *Aerosol General Dynamic Equation* (GDE) characterizes the evolution of the number density of particles in an aerosol due to these processes.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] As particles and droplets in an aerosol collide with one another, they may undergo coalescence or aggregation.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] This process leads to a change in the aerosol particle-size distribution, with the mode increasing in diameter as total number of particles decreases.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] On occasion, particles may shatter apart into numerous smaller particles; however, this process usually occurs primarily in particles too large for consideration as aerosols.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] where $\lambda$ is the mean free path of the suspending gas and d is the diameter of the particle.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] For particles in the *free molecular regime*, *Kn* >> 1; particles small compared to the mean free path of the suspending gas.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] In this regime, particles interact with the suspending gas through a series of "ballistic" collisions with gas molecules.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] As such, they behave similarly to gas molecules, tending to follow streamlines and diffusing rapidly through Brownian motion.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] where *a* is the particle radius, *P*∞ and *PA* are the pressures far from the droplet and at the surface of the droplet respectively, *kb* is the Boltzmann constant, *T* is the temperature, *CA* is mean thermal velocity and *α* is mass accommodation coefficient.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The derivation of this equation assumes constant pressure and constant diffusion coefficient.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Particles are in the *continuum regime* when Kn << 1.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] In this regime, the particles are big compared to the mean free path of the suspending gas, meaning that the suspending gas acts as a continuous fluid flowing round the particle.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The *transition regime* contains all the particles in between the free molecular and continuum regimes or *Kn* ≈ 1.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The forces experienced by a particle are a complex combination of interactions with individual gas molecules and macroscopic interactions.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] where *I*cont is the mass flux in the continuum regime.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] This formula is called the Fuchs-Sutugin interpolation formula.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] These equations do not take into account the heat release effect.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Aerosol partitioning theory governs condensation on and evaporation from an aerosol surface, respectively.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Condensation of mass causes the mode of the particle-size distributions of the aerosol to increase; conversely, evaporation causes the mode to decrease.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Nucleation is the process of forming aerosol mass from the condensation of a gaseous precursor, specifically a vapor.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Net condensation of the vapor requires supersaturation, a partial pressure greater than its vapor pressure.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Chemical reactions may increase the partial pressure of a gas or lower its vapor pressure.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The addition of additional vapor to the system may lower the equilibrium vapor pressure according to Raoult's law.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] There are two types of nucleation processes.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Gases preferentially condense onto surfaces of pre-existing aerosol particles, known as **heterogeneous nucleation**.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] This process causes the diameter at the mode of particle-size distribution to increase with constant number concentration.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] With sufficiently high supersaturation and no suitable surfaces, particles may condense in the absence of a pre-existing surface, known as **homogeneous nucleation**.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] This results in the addition of very small, rapidly growing particles to the particle-size distribution.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Water coats particles in aerosols, making them *activated*, usually in the context of forming a cloud droplet (such as natural cloud seeding by aerosols from trees in a forest).
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Following the Kelvin equation (based on the curvature of liquid droplets), smaller particles need a higher ambient relative humidity to maintain equilibrium than larger particles do.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] where $p_{s}$ is the saturation vapor pressure above a particle at equilibrium (around a curved liquid droplet), *p*0 is the saturation vapor pressure (flat surface of the same liquid) and *S* is the saturation ratio.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] where *rp* droplet radius, *σ* surface tension of droplet, *ρ* density of liquid, *M* molar mass, *T* temperature, and *R* molar gas constant.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Aerosols can either be measured in-situ or with remote sensing techniques either ground-based on airborne-based.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Particles can deposit in the nose, mouth, pharynx and larynx (the head airways region), deeper within the respiratory tract (from the trachea to the terminal bronchioles), or in the alveolar region.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The location of deposition of aerosol particles within the respiratory system strongly determines the health effects of exposure to such aerosols.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] This phenomenon led people to invent aerosol samplers that select a subset of the aerosol particles that reach certain parts of the respiratory system.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Examples of these subsets of the particle-size distribution of an aerosol, important in occupational health, include the inhalable, thoracic, and respirable fractions.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The fraction that can enter each part of the respiratory system depends on the deposition of particles in the upper parts of the airway.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The inhalable fraction of particles, defined as the proportion of particles originally in the air that can enter the nose or mouth, depends on external wind speed and direction and on the particle-size distribution by aerodynamic diameter.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The thoracic fraction is the proportion of the particles in ambient aerosol that can reach the thorax or chest region.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The respirable fraction is the proportion of particles in the air that can reach the alveolar region.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] To measure the respirable fraction of particles in air, a pre-collector is used with a sampling filter.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The pre-collector excludes particles as the airways remove particles from inhaled air.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The sampling filter collects the particles for measurement.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] It is common to use cyclonic separation for the pre-collector, but other techniques include impactors, horizontal elutriators, and large pore membrane filters.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] Two alternative size-selective criteria, often used in atmospheric monitoring, are PM10 and PM2.5.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] PM10 is defined by ISO as *particles which pass through a size-selective inlet with a 50% efficiency cut-off at 10 μm aerodynamic diameter* and PM2.5 as *particles which pass through a size-selective inlet with a 50% efficiency cut-off at 2.5 μm aerodynamic diameter*.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] PM10 corresponds to the "thoracic convention" as defined in ISO 7708:1995, Clause 6; PM2.5 corresponds to the "high-risk respirable convention" as defined in ISO 7708:1995, 7.1.
[src:air-quality-index/aerodynamic-diameter] The United States Environmental Protection Agency replaced the older standards for particulate matter based on Total Suspended Particulate with another standard based on PM10 in 1987 and then introduced standards for PM2.5 (also known as fine particulate matter) in 1997.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Agent Orange was produced in the United States beginning in the late 1940s and was used in industrial agriculture, and was also sprayed along railroads and power lines to control undergrowth in forests.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Nine chemical companies produced it, including Dow Chemical Company and Monsanto Company.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Agent Orange exposure is linked to increased rates of birth defects, malignancies, cardiovascular diseases, and diabetes.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The science on the causality between exposure and health problems remains incomplete.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The U.S. government has documented cases of leukemia, Hodgkin's lymphoma, and various kinds of cancer in exposed U.S. veterans, but not concluded a causal relationship or a plausible biological carcinogenic mechanism.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention identified an increase in the rate of birth defects of the children of exposed U.S. veterans.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The impact of Agent Orange in Vietnam includes health and ecological effects.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The government of Vietnam defined victims of Agent Orange by looking at where they live, their family history, and if the health problems have been linked to Agent Orange.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The U.S. government has described these figures as unreliable.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Agent Orange has also caused enormous environmental damage in Vietnam.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] This has been described by numerous lawyers, historians and other academics as ecocide.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Defoliants eroded tree cover and seedling forest stock, making reforestation difficult in numerous areas.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Animal species diversity is sharply reduced in contrast with unsprayed areas.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The use of Agent Orange in Vietnam resulted in numerous legal actions.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The United Nations ratified General Assembly Resolution 31/72 in 1976 and the Environmental Modification Convention in 1977.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Under the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) definition, Agent Orange is not considered a chemical weapon as it was not used to cause intentional death or harm to humans through its toxic properties.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Lawsuits have been filed on behalf of both U.S. and Vietnamese veterans and civilians seeking compensation for damages.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The active ingredient of Agent Orange was an equal mixture of two phenoxy herbicides – 2,4-dichlorophenoxyacetic acid (2,4-D) and 2,4,5-trichlorophenoxyacetic acid (2,4,5-T) – in iso-octyl ester form, which contained traces of the dioxin 2,3,7,8-tetrachlorodibenzo-*p*-dioxin (TCDD).
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] TCDD was a trace, but significant, contaminant of Agent Orange (typically 2–3 ppm, ranging from 50 ppb to 50 ppm).
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] TCDD is the most toxic of the dioxins and is classified as a human carcinogen by the U.S.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The fat-soluble nature of TCDD causes it to accumulate easily in the food chain, and can enter the body readily through physical contact or ingestion.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] When TCDD binds to cytoplasmic aryl hydrocarbon receptor (AhR), a transcription factor, the protein translocates to the cell nucleus, where it influences gene expression.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] According to U.S. government reports, if not bound chemically to a biological surface such as soil, leaves or grass, Agent Orange dries quickly after spraying and breaks down within hours to days when exposed to sunlight and is no longer harmful.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Several herbicides were developed as part of efforts by the United States and the United Kingdom to create herbicidal weapons for use during World War II.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] These included 2,4-D, 2,4,5-T, MCPA (2-methyl-4-chlorophenoxyacetic acid, 1414B and 1414A, recoded LN-8 and LN-32), and isopropyl phenylcarbamate (1313, recoded LN-33).
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] While a graduate and post-graduate student at the University of Illinois, Galston's research and dissertation focused on finding a chemical means to make soybeans flower and fruit earlier.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] He discovered both that 2,3,5-triiodobenzoic acid (TIBA) would speed up the flowering of soybeans and that in higher concentrations it would defoliate the soybeans.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] From these studies arose the concept of using aerial applications of herbicides to destroy enemy crops to disrupt their food supply.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Army ran tests of various 2,4-D and 2,4,5-T mixtures at the Bushnell Army Airfield in Florida.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] As a result, the U.S. began a full-scale production of 2,4-D and 2,4,5-T and would have used it against Japan in 1946 during Operation Downfall if the war had continued.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] In the years after the war, the U.S. tested 1,100 compounds, and field trials of the more promising ones were done at British stations in India and Australia, in order to establish their effects in tropical conditions, as well as at the U.S. testing ground in Florida.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Between 1950 and 1952, trials were conducted in Tanganyika, at Kikore and Stunyansa, to test arboricides and defoliants under tropical conditions.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The chemicals involved were 2,4-D, 2,4,5-T, and endothall (3,6-endoxohexahydrophthalic acid).
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] During 1952–53, the unit supervised the aerial spraying of 2,4,5-T in Kenya to assess the value of defoliants in the eradication of tsetse fly.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] In Malaya, the local unit of Imperial Chemical Industries researched defoliants as weed killers for rubber plantations.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Roadside ambushes by the Malayan National Liberation Army were a danger to the British Commonwealth forces during the Malayan Emergency, several trials were made to defoliate vegetation that might hide ambush sites, but hand removal was found cheaper.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] A detailed account of how the British experimented with the spraying of herbicides was written by two scientists, E.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Woodford of Agricultural Research Council's Unit of Experimental Agronomy and H.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] After the Malayan Emergency ended in 1960, the U.S. considered the British precedent in deciding that the use of defoliants was a legal tactic of warfare.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Secretary of State Dean Rusk advised President John F.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Kennedy that the British had established a precedent for warfare with herbicides in Malaya.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] In mid-1961, President Ngo Dinh Diem of South Vietnam asked the United States to help defoliate the lush jungle that was providing cover to the North Vietnamese army and Viet Cong.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] In August of that year, the Republic of Vietnam Air Force conducted herbicide operations with American help.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Diem's request launched a policy debate in the White House and the State and Defense Departments.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Many U.S. officials supported herbicide operations, pointing out that the British had already used herbicides and defoliants in Malaya during the 1950s.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] In November 1961, Kennedy authorized the start of Operation Ranch Hand, the codename for the United States Air Force's herbicide program in Vietnam.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The herbicide operations were formally directed by the government of South Vietnam.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] As the British did in Malaya, the goal of the U.S. was to defoliate rural/forested land, depriving guerrillas of food and concealment and clearing sensitive areas such as around base perimeters and possible ambush sites along roads and canals.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Huntington argued that the program was also part of a policy of forced draft urbanization, which aimed to destroy the ability of peasants to support themselves in the countryside, forcing them to flee to the U.S.-dominated cities, depriving the guerrillas of their rural support base.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Agent Orange was usually sprayed from helicopters or from low-flying C-123 Provider aircraft planes, fitted with sprayers and "MC-1 Hourglass" pump systems and 1,000 U.S. gal (3,800 L; 830 imp gal) chemical tanks.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Spray runs were also conducted from trucks, boats, and backpack sprayers.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The first batch of herbicides was unloaded at Tan Son Nhut Air Base in South Vietnam on January 9, 1962.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Air Force records show that at least 6,542 spraying missions took place throughout Operation Ranch Hand.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] By 1971, 12 percent of the total area of South Vietnam had been sprayed with defoliating chemicals, at an average concentration of 13 times the recommended U.S.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Department of Agriculture application rate for domestic use.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] In South Vietnam alone, an estimated 39,000 sq mi (100,000 km2) of agricultural land was ultimately destroyed.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] In some areas, TCDD concentrations in soil and water were hundreds of times greater than the levels considered safe by the EPA.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The campaign destroyed 7,700 sq mi (20,000 km2) of upland and mangrove forests and thousands of square kilometres of crops.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Overall, more than 20% of South Vietnam's forests were sprayed at least once over the nine years.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] 3.2% of South Vietnam's cultivated land was sprayed at least once between 1965 and 1971.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] 90% of herbicide use was directed at defoliation.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The U.S. military began targeting food crops in October 1962, primarily using Agent Blue; the American public was not made aware of the crop destruction programs until 1965 (and it was then believed that crop spraying had begun that spring).
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] In 1965, 42% of all herbicide spraying was dedicated to food crops.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Congress were told, "crop destruction is understood to be the more important purpose ... but the emphasis is usually given to the jungle defoliation in public mention of the program." The first official acknowledgment of the programs came from the State Department in March 1966.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] When crops were destroyed, the National Liberation Front would compensate for the loss of food by confiscating more food from local villages.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Some military personnel reported being told they were destroying crops used to feed guerrillas, only to later discover, most of the destroyed food was actually produced to support the local civilian population.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Wil Verwey wrote in 1977 that ecologist Arthur H.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Westing, during a 1969 visit to the Quang Ngai province, had been told that 15 crop destruction missions had been approved in the province for 1970.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] According to Verwey, these missions would have been enough to cover 85% of crop lands in the province and would have caused famine and left hundreds of thousands of people without food or malnourished although it was unclear if all the approved missions were actually carried out.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] According to a report by the American Association for the Advancement of Science, the herbicide campaign had disrupted the food supply of more than 600,000 people by 1970.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Many experts at the time, including plant physiologist and bioethicist Arthur Galston, opposed herbicidal warfare because of concerns about the side effects to humans and the environment from indiscriminately spraying the chemical over a wide area.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] As early as 1966, resolutions were introduced to the United Nations charging that the U.S. was violating the 1925 Geneva Protocol, which regulated the use of chemical and biological weapons in international conflicts.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The U.S. defeated most of the resolutions, arguing that Agent Orange was not a chemical or a biological weapon as it was considered an herbicide and a defoliant and it was used in effort to destroy plant crops and to deprive the enemy of concealment and not meant to target human beings.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The U.S. delegation argued that a weapon, by definition, is any device used to injure, defeat, or destroy living beings, structures, or systems, and Agent Orange did not qualify under that definition.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] It also argued that if the U.S. were to be charged for using Agent Orange, then the United Kingdom and its Commonwealth nations should be charged since they also used it widely during the Malayan Emergency in the 1950s.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] A study carried out by the Bionetic Research Laboratories between 1965 and 1968 found malformations in test animals caused by 2,4,5-T, a component of Agent Orange.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The study was later brought to the attention of the White House in October 1969.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Other studies reported similar results and the Department of Defense began to reduce the herbicide operation.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] On April 15, 1970, it was announced that the use of Agent Orange was suspended.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Two brigades of the Americal Division in the summer of 1970 continued to use Agent Orange for crop destruction in violation of the suspension.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] An investigation led to disciplinary action against the brigade and division commanders because they had falsified reports to hide its use.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Defoliation and crop destruction were completely stopped by June 30, 1971.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] There are various types of cancer associated with Agent Orange, including chronic B-cell leukemia, Hodgkin's lymphoma, multiple myeloma, non-Hodgkin lymphoma, prostate cancer, respiratory cancer, lung cancer, and soft tissue sarcomas.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Some literature claims that neither Agent Orange nor its contaminants are carcinogenic in humans.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The government of Vietnam states that 4 million of its citizens were exposed to Agent Orange, and as many as 3 million have suffered illnesses because of it; these figures include their children who were exposed.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The Red Cross of Vietnam estimates that up to 1 million people are disabled or have health problems due to Agent Orange contamination.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The United States government has challenged these figures as being unreliable.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Nguyen Viet Nhan, children in the areas where Agent Orange was used have been affected and have multiple health problems, including cleft palate, mental disabilities, hernias, and extra fingers and toes.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] In the 1970s, high levels of dioxin were found in the breast milk of South Vietnamese women, and in the blood of U.S. military personnel who had served in Vietnam.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The most affected zones are the mountainous area along Truong Son (Long Mountains) and the border between Vietnam and Cambodia.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The affected residents are living in substandard conditions with many genetic diseases.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] In 2006, Anh Duc Ngo and colleagues of the University of Texas Health Science Center published a meta-analysis that exposed a large amount of heterogeneity (different findings) between studies, a finding consistent with a lack of consensus on the issue.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Despite this, statistical analysis of the studies they examined resulted in data that the increase in birth defects/relative risk (RR) from exposure to agent orange/dioxin "appears" to be on the order of 3 in Vietnamese-funded studies, but 1.29 in the rest of the world.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] There is data near the threshold of statistical significance suggesting Agent Orange contributes to stillbirths, cleft palate, and neural tube defects, with spina bifida being the most statistically significant defect.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The large discrepancy in RR between Vietnamese studies and those in the rest of the world has been ascribed to bias in the Vietnamese studies.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Twenty-eight of the former U.S. military bases in Vietnam, where the herbicides were stored and loaded onto airplanes, may still have high levels of dioxins in the soil, posing a health threat to the surrounding communities.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Extensive testing for dioxin contamination has been conducted at the former U.S. airbases in Da Nang, Phù Cát District and Biên Hòa.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Some of the soil and sediment on the bases have extremely high levels of dioxin, requiring remediation.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The Da Nang Air Base has dioxin contamination up to 350 times higher than international recommendations for action.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The contaminated soil and sediment continue to affect the citizens of Vietnam, poisoning their food chain and causing illnesses, serious skin diseases and a variety of cancers in the lungs, larynx, and prostate.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] While in Vietnam, U.S. and Free World Military Assistance Forces soldiers were told not to worry about Agent Orange and were persuaded that the chemical was harmless.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] After returning home, Vietnam veterans from all countries that served began to suspect their ill health or the instances of their wives having miscarriages or children born with birth defects might be related to Agent Orange and the other toxic herbicides to which they had been exposed in Vietnam.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] By April 1993, the Department of Veterans Affairs had compensated only 486 victims, although it had received disability claims from 39,419 soldiers who had been exposed to Agent Orange while serving in Vietnam.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Only in 1994 did the Australian government finally admit that it was true that defoliants had been used in areas of Vietnam where Australian forces operated, and the effects of these may have been detrimental to some Vietnam veterans and their children.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] It was only in 2015 that the official Australian War Memorial accepted rewriting the official history of Australia's involvement in the Vietnam War to acknowledge that Australian soldiers were exposed to defoliants used in Vietnam.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] New Zealand was even slower to correct its error, with the government going as far as to deny the legitimacy of the Australian reports in a report called the "McLeod Report," published by Veterans Affairs NZ in 2001, thus infuriating New Zealand veterans and those associated with their cause.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] In 2008, the New Zealand government finally admitted that New Zealanders had been exposed to Agent Orange while serving in Vietnam, and the experience was responsible for detrimental health conditions in veterans and their children.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Amendments to the memorandum made in 2021 meant that more veterans were eligible for an ex gratia payment of NZ$40,000.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Starting in the early 1990s, the federal government directed the Institute of Medicine (IOM), renamed the National Academy of Medicine, to issue reports every 2 years on the health effects of Agent Orange and similar herbicides.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] First published in 1994 and titled *Veterans and Agent Orange*, the IOM reports assess the risk of both cancer and non-cancer health effects.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Each health effect is categorized by evidence of association based on available research data.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The last update was published in 2016, entitled *Veterans and Agent Orange: Update 2014*.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The report shows sufficient evidence of an association with soft tissue sarcoma; non-Hodgkin lymphoma (NHL); Hodgkin disease; Chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL); including hairy cell leukemia and other chronic B-cell leukemias.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Limited or suggested evidence of an association was linked with respiratory cancers (lung, bronchus, trachea, larynx); prostate cancer; multiple myeloma; and bladder cancer.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Numerous other cancers were determined to have inadequate or insufficient evidence of links to Agent Orange.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] At the request of the Veterans Administration, the Institute of Medicine evaluated whether service in these C-123 aircraft could have plausibly exposed soldiers and been detrimental to their health.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Their report *Post-Vietnam Dioxin Exposure in Agent Orange-Contaminated C-123 Aircraft* confirmed it.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Publications by the United States Public Health Service have shown that Vietnam veterans, overall, have increased rates of cancer, and nerve, digestive, skin, and respiratory disorders.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention notes that in particular, there are higher rates of acute/chronic leukemia, Hodgkin's lymphoma and non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, throat cancer, prostate cancer, lung cancer, colon cancer, ischemic heart disease, soft tissue sarcoma, and liver cancer.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Except liver cancer, these are the same conditions the U.S.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Veterans Administration has determined may be associated with exposure to Agent Orange/dioxin and are on the list of conditions eligible for compensation and treatment.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Military personnel who were involved in storage, mixture and transportation (including aircraft mechanics), and actual use of the chemicals were probably among those who received the heaviest exposures.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Military members who served on Okinawa also claim to have been exposed to the chemical, but there is no verifiable evidence to corroborate these claims.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Some studies have suggested that veterans exposed to Agent Orange may be more at risk of developing prostate cancer and potentially more than twice as likely to develop higher-grade, more lethal prostate cancers.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] However, a critical analysis of these studies and 35 others consistently found that there was no significant increase in prostate cancer incidence or mortality in those exposed to Agent Orange or 2,3,7,8-tetracholorodibenzo-*p*-dioxin.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] During the Vietnam War, the United States fought the North Vietnamese, and their allies, in Laos and Cambodia, including heavy bombing campaigns.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] They also sprayed large quantities of Agent Orange in each of those countries.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] One noteworthy exception, according to the U.S.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] About 17.8% or 12,000 square miles (31,000 km2; 3,100,000 ha) of the total forested area of Vietnam was sprayed during the war, which disrupted the ecological equilibrium.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The persistent nature of dioxins, erosion caused by loss of tree cover, and loss of seedling forest stock meant that reforestation was difficult (or impossible) in many areas.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Many defoliated forest areas were quickly invaded by aggressive pioneer species (such as bamboo and cogon grass), making forest regeneration difficult and unlikely.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Animal species diversity was also impacted; in one study a Harvard biologist found 24 species of birds and 5 species of mammals in a sprayed forest, while in two adjacent sections of unsprayed forest there were, respectively, 145 and 170 species of birds and 30 and 55 species of mammals.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The environmental destruction caused by this defoliation has been described by Swedish Prime Minister Olof Palme, lawyers, historians and other academics as an ecocide.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Dioxins from Agent Orange have persisted in the Vietnamese environment since the war, settling in the soil and sediment and entering the food chain through animals and fish that feed in the contaminated areas.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The movement of dioxins through the food web has resulted in bioconcentration and biomagnification.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] The areas most heavily contaminated with dioxins are former U.S. air bases.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] American policy during the Vietnam War was to destroy crops, accepting the sociopolitical impact that that would have.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p01] Crops were deliberately sprayed with Agent Orange and areas were bulldozed clear of vegetation forcing many rural civilians to cities.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The extensive environmental damage that resulted from usage of the herbicide prompted the United Nations to pass Resolution 31/72 and ratify the Environmental Modification Convention.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Many states do not regard this as a complete ban on the use of herbicides and defoliants in warfare, but it does require case-by-case consideration.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] This exception voids any protection of any military and civilian personnel from a napalm attack or something like Agent Orange, and it has been argued that it was clearly designed to cover situations like U.S. tactics in Vietnam.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Since at least 1978, several lawsuits have been filed against the companies which produced Agent Orange, among them Dow Chemical, Monsanto, and Diamond Shamrock.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In 1978, army veteran Paul Reutershan sued Dow Chemical for $10 million, after he was diagnosed with terminal cancer that he believed was a result of Agent Orange exposure.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] After Reutershan died in December 1978, his attorneys added additional plaintiffs and refiled the lawsuit as a class action.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] That lawsuit would eventually represent thousands of veterans, and was considered one of the largest and most complex lawsuits ever brought in the US at that time.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Attorney Hy Mayerson was an early pioneer in Agent Orange litigation, working with environmental attorney Victor Yannacone in 1980 on the first class-action suits against wartime manufacturers of Agent Orange.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The corporate defendants sought to escape culpability by blaming everything on the U.S. government.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Hartz, as their principal client, filed the first U.S.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Agent Orange class-action lawsuit in Pennsylvania, for the injuries military personnel in Vietnam suffered through exposure to toxic dioxins in the defoliant.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Attorney Mayerson co-wrote the brief that certified the Agent Orange Product Liability action as a class action, the largest ever filed as of its filing.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The firm also located and supplied critical research to the veterans' lead expert, Dr.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The chemical companies involved denied that there was a link between Agent Orange and the veterans' medical problems.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] However, on May 7, 1984, seven chemical companies settled the class-action suit out of court just hours before jury selection was to begin.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The companies agreed to pay $180 million as compensation if the veterans dropped all claims against them.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Slightly over 45% of the sum was ordered to be paid by Monsanto alone.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Many veterans who were victims of Agent Orange exposure were outraged the case had been settled instead of going to court and felt they had been betrayed by the lawyers.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] "Fairness Hearings" were held in five major American cities, where veterans and their families discussed their reactions to the settlement and condemned the actions of the lawyers and courts, demanding the case be heard before a jury of their peers.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Weinstein refused the appeals, claiming the settlement was "fair and just".
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] By 1989, the veterans' fears were confirmed when it was decided how the money from the settlement would be paid out.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] A totally disabled Vietnam veteran would receive a maximum of $12,000 spread out over the course of 10 years.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Furthermore, by accepting the settlement payments, disabled veterans would become ineligible for many state benefits that provided far more monetary support than the settlement, such as food stamps, public assistance, and government pensions.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] A widow of a Vietnam veteran who died of Agent Orange exposure would receive $3,700.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] On 22 August 2024, the Court of Appeal of Paris dismissed an appeal filed by Tran To Nga against 14 US corporations that supplied Agent Orange for the US army during the war in Vietnam.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The lawyers said that Nga will take her case to France's highest appeals court.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Only military veterans from the United States and its allies in the war have won compensation so far.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Some of the agrochemical companies in the U.S. have compensated U.S. veterans, but not to Vietnamese victims.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In 1980, New Jersey created the New Jersey Agent Orange Commission, the first state commission created to study its effects.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The commission's research project in association with Rutgers University was called "The Pointman Project".
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] It was disbanded by Governor Christine Todd Whitman in 1996.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] During the first phase of the project, commission researchers devised ways to determine trace dioxin levels in blood.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Before this, such levels could only be found in the adipose (fat) tissue.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The project studied dioxin (TCDD) levels in blood as well as in adipose tissue in a small group of Vietnam veterans who had been exposed to Agent Orange and compared them to those of a matched control group; the levels were found to be higher in the exposed group.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The second phase of the project continued to examine and compare dioxin levels in various groups of Vietnam veterans, including Soldiers, Marines, and Brownwater Naval personnel.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In 1991, Congress enacted the Agent Orange Act, giving the Department of Veterans Affairs the authority to declare certain conditions "presumptive" to exposure to Agent Orange/dioxin, making these veterans who served in Vietnam eligible to receive treatment and compensation for these conditions.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The authority for the National Academy of Sciences reviews and addition of any new diseases to the presumptive list by the VA expired in 2015 under the sunset clause of the Agent Orange Act of 1991.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Through this process, the list of 'presumptive' conditions has grown since 1991, and currently the U.S.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] This list now includes B cell leukemias, such as hairy cell leukemia, Parkinson's disease and ischemic heart disease, these last three having been added on August 31, 2010.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Several highly placed individuals in government are voicing concerns about whether some of the diseases on the list should, in fact, actually have been included.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In 2011, an appraisal of the 20-year long *Air Force Health Study* that began in 1982 indicates that the results of the AFHS as they pertain to Agent Orange, do not provide evidence of disease in the Operation Ranch Hand veterans caused by "their elevated levels of exposure to Agent Orange".
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The VA initially denied the applications of post-Vietnam C-123 aircrew veterans because, as veterans without "boots on the ground" service in Vietnam, they were not covered under VA's interpretation of "exposed".
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In June 2015, the Secretary of Veterans Affairs issued an Interim final rule providing presumptive service connection for post-Vietnam C-123 aircrews, maintenance staff and aeromedical evacuation crews.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The VA now provides medical care and disability compensation for the recognized list of Agent Orange illnesses.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In 2002, Vietnam and the U.S. held a joint conference on Human Health and Environmental Impacts of Agent Orange.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] National Institute of Environmental Health Sciences (NIEHS) began scientific exchanges between the U.S. and Vietnam, and began discussions for a joint research project on the human health impacts of Agent Orange.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] These negotiations broke down in 2005, when neither side could agree on the research protocol, and the research project was canceled.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] More progress has been made on the environmental front.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In 2005, the first U.S.-Vietnam workshop on remediation of dioxin was held.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Starting in 2005, the EPA began to work with the Vietnamese government to measure the level of dioxin at the Da Nang Air Base.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Also in 2005, the Joint Advisory Committee on Agent Orange, made up of representatives of Vietnamese and U.S. government agencies, was established.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The committee has been meeting yearly to explore areas of scientific cooperation, technical assistance and environmental remediation of dioxin.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] A breakthrough in the diplomatic stalemate on this issue occurred as a result of United States President George W.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Bush's state visit to Vietnam in November 2006.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The appropriation was renewed in the fiscal year 2009 and again in FY 2010.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] An additional $12 million was appropriated in the fiscal year 2010 in the Supplemental Appropriations Act and a total of $18.5 million appropriated for fiscal year 2011.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Secretary of State Hillary Clinton stated during a visit to Hanoi in October 2010 that the U.S. government would begin work on the clean-up of dioxin contamination at the Da Nang Airbase.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In June 2011, a ceremony was held at Da Nang airport to mark the start of U.S.-funded decontamination of dioxin hotspots in Vietnam.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Thirty-two million dollars has so far been allocated by the U.S.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] A $43 million project began in the summer of 2012, as Vietnam and the U.S. forge closer ties to boost trade and counter China's rising influence in the disputed South China Sea.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Dow Chemical and Monsanto were the two largest producers of Agent Orange for the U.S. military and were named in the suit, along with the dozens of other companies (Diamond Shamrock, Uniroyal, Thompson Chemicals, Hercules, etc.).
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Weinstein of the Eastern District – who had presided over the 1984 U.S. veterans class-action lawsuit – dismissed the lawsuit, ruling there was no legal basis for the plaintiffs' claims.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] He concluded Agent Orange was not considered a poison under international humanitarian law at the time of its use by the U.S.; the U.S. was not prohibited from using it as a herbicide; and the companies that produced the substance were not liable for the method of its use by the government.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The U.S. government was also not a party in the lawsuit because of sovereign immunity, and the court ruled the chemical companies, as contractors of the U.S. government, shared the same immunity.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The case was appealed and heard by the Second Circuit Court of Appeals in Manhattan on June 18, 2007.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Three judges on the court upheld Weinstein's ruling to dismiss the case.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] They ruled that, though the herbicides contained a dioxin (a known poison), they were not intended to be used as a poison on humans.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Therefore, they were not considered a chemical weapon and thus not a violation of international law.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] A further review of the case by the entire panel of judges of the Court of Appeals also confirmed this decision.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The lawyers for the Vietnamese filed a petition to the U.S.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] On March 2, 2009, the Supreme Court denied certiorari and declined to reconsider the ruling of the Court of Appeals.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] To assist those who have been affected by Agent Orange/dioxin, the Vietnamese have established "peace villages", which each host between 50 and 100 victims, giving them medical and psychological help.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] As of 2006, there were 11 such villages, thus granting some social protection to fewer than a thousand victims.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] U.S. veterans of the war in Vietnam and individuals who are aware and sympathetic to the impacts of Agent Orange have supported these programs in Vietnam.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] An international group of veterans from the U.S. and its allies during the Vietnam War working with their former enemy—veterans from the Vietnam Veterans Association—established the Vietnam Friendship Village outside of Hanoi.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The center provides medical care, rehabilitation and vocational training for children and veterans from Vietnam who have been affected by Agent Orange.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In 1998, The Vietnam Red Cross established the Vietnam Agent Orange Victims Fund to provide direct assistance to families throughout Vietnam that have been affected.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In 2004, the Vietnam Association of Victims of Agent Orange (VAVA) was formed.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In addition to filing the lawsuit against the chemical companies, VAVA provides medical care, rehabilitation services and financial assistance to those injured by Agent Orange.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The Vietnamese government provides small monthly stipends to more than 200,000 Vietnamese people believed to be affected by the herbicides; this totaled $40.8 million in 2008.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] On June 16, 2010, members of the U.S.-Vietnam Dialogue Group on Agent Orange/Dioxin unveiled a comprehensive 10-year Declaration and Plan of Action to address the toxic legacy of Agent Orange and other herbicides in Vietnam.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] On September 16, 2010, Senator Patrick Leahy acknowledged the work of the Dialogue Group by releasing a statement on the floor of the United States Senate.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The statement urges the U.S. government to take the Plan of Action's recommendations into account in developing a multi-year plan of activities to address the Agent Orange/dioxin legacy.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In 2008, Australian researcher Jean Williams claimed that cancer rates in Innisfail, Queensland, were 10 times higher than the state average because of secret testing of Agent Orange by the Australian military scientists during the Vietnam War.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Williams, who had won the Order of Australia medal for her research on the effects of chemicals on U.S. war veterans, based her allegations on Australian government reports found in the Australian War Memorial's archives.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] A former soldier, Ted Bosworth, backed up the claims, saying that he had been involved in the secret testing.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Neither Williams nor Bosworth has produced verifiable evidence to support their claims.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The Queensland health department determined that cancer rates in Innisfail were no higher than those in other parts of the state.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The U.S. military, with the permission of the Canadian government, tested herbicides, including Agent Orange, in the forests near Canadian Forces Base Gagetown in New Brunswick.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In 2007, the government of Canada offered a one-time ex gratia payment of $20,000 as compensation for Agent Orange exposure at CFB Gagetown.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] On July 12, 2005, Merchant Law Group, on behalf of over 1,100 Canadian veterans and civilians who were living in and around CFB Gagetown, filed a lawsuit to pursue class action litigation concerning Agent Orange and Agent Purple with the Federal Court of Canada.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] On August 4, 2009, the case was rejected by the court, citing lack of evidence.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In 2007, the Canadian government announced that a research and fact-finding program initiated in 2005 had found the base was safe.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] On February 17, 2011, the *Toronto Star* revealed that Agent Orange had been employed to clear extensive plots of Crown land in Northern Ontario.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] An analysis of chemicals present in the island's soil, together with resolutions passed by Guam's legislature, suggest that Agent Orange was among the herbicides routinely used on and around Andersen Air Force Base and Naval Air Station Agana.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Despite the evidence, the Department of Defense continues to deny that Agent Orange was stored or used on Guam.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Agent Orange was used in South Korea in the late 1960s and in 1999, about 20,000 South Koreans filed two separated lawsuits against U.S. companies, seeking more than $5 billion in damages.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] After losing a decision in 2002, they filed an appeal.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In January 2006, the South Korean Appeals Court ordered Dow Chemical and Monsanto to pay $62 million in compensation to about 6,800 people.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The ruling acknowledged that "the defendants failed to ensure safety as the defoliants manufactured by the defendants had higher levels of dioxins than standard", and, quoting the U.S.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] National Academy of Science report, declared that there was a "causal relationship" between Agent Orange and a range of diseases, including several cancers.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The judges failed to acknowledge "the relationship between the chemical and peripheral neuropathy, the disease most widespread among Agent Orange victims".
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In 2011, the United States local press KPHO-TV in Phoenix, Arizona, alleged that in 1978 that the United States Army had buried 250 55-gallon drums (13,750 U.S. gal (52,000 L; 11,450 imp gal)) of Agent Orange in Camp Carroll, the U.S.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Army base located in Gyeongsangbuk-do, South Korea.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Currently, veterans who provide evidence meeting VA requirements for service in Vietnam and who can medically establish that anytime after this 'presumptive exposure' they developed any medical problems on the list of presumptive diseases, may receive compensation from the VA.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Certain veterans who served in South Korea and can prove they were assigned to certain specified areas around the Korean Demilitarized Zone, during a specific time frame, are afforded similar presumption.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] What is fact is that from 1962 until 1987, 2,4,5T herbicide was manufactured at the Ivon Watkins-Dow plant for domestic use in New Zealand.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] It was widely used by farmers and in New Zealand agriculture as a weed killer.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] This fact was the basis of a 2005 New Zealand Media story that claimed that the herbicide had been allegedly exported to U.S. military bases in South East Asia.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] However the claim was not proven, a fact which the Media did not subsequently report.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] There have been continuing claims, as yet unproven, that the suburb of Paritutu has also been polluted.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] However, the agriscience company Corteva (which split from DowDupont in 2019) agreed to clean up the Paritutu site in September 2022.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Herbicide persistence studies of Agents Orange and White were conducted in the Philippines.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Air Force operation to remove Herbicide Orange from Vietnam in 1972 was named Operation Pacer IVY, while the operation to destroy the Agent Orange stored at Johnston Atoll in 1977 was named Operation Pacer HO.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Operation Pacer IVY collected Agent Orange in South Vietnam and removed it in 1972 aboard the ship MV Transpacific for storage on Johnston Atoll.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The EPA reports that 6,800,000 L (1,800,000 U.S. gal) of Herbicide Orange was stored at Johnston Island in the Pacific and 1,800,000 L (480,000 U.S. gal) at Gulfport, Mississippi.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Research and studies were initiated to find a safe method to destroy the materials, and it was discovered that they could be incinerated safely under special conditions of temperature and dwell time.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] However, these herbicides were expensive, and the Air Force wanted to resell its surplus instead of dumping it at sea.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Among many methods tested, a possibility of salvaging the herbicides by reprocessing and filtering out the TCDD contaminant with carbonized (charcoaled) coconut fibers.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] This concept was then tested in 1976, and a pilot plant constructed at Gulfport.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] As of 2004, some records of the storage and disposition of Agent Orange at Johnston Atoll have been associated with the historical records of Operation Red Hat.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] There have been dozens of reports in the press about the use and/or storage of military-formulated herbicides on Okinawa that are based upon statements by former U.S. service members that had been stationed on the island, photographs, government records, and unearthed storage barrels.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Department of Defense has denied these allegations with statements by military officials and spokespersons, as well as a January 2013 report authored by Dr.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Alvin Young that was released in April 2013.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In particular, the 2013 report rebuts articles written by journalist Jon Mitchell as well as a statement from "An Ecological Assessment of Johnston Atoll" a 2003 publication produced by the United States Army Chemical Materials Agency that states, "in 1972, the U.S.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Agent Orange was tested by the United States in Thailand during the Vietnam War.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In 1999, buried drums were uncovered and confirmed to be Agent Orange.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Workers who uncovered the drums fell ill while upgrading the airport near Hua Hin District, 100 km south of Bangkok.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Vietnam-era veterans whose service involved duty on or near the perimeters of military bases in Thailand anytime between February 28, 1961, and May 7, 1975, may have been exposed to herbicides and may qualify for VA benefits.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] A declassified Department of Defense report written in 1973, suggests that there was a significant use of herbicides on the fenced-in perimeters of military bases in Thailand to remove foliage that provided cover for enemy forces.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In 2013, the VA determined that herbicides used on the Thailand base perimeters may have been tactical and procured from Vietnam, or a strong, commercial type resembling tactical herbicides.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In 1971, the C-123 aircraft used for spraying Agent Orange were returned to the United States and assigned various East Coast USAF Reserve squadrons, and then employed in traditional airlift missions between 1972 and 1982.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In 1994, testing by the Air Force identified some former spray aircraft as "heavily contaminated" with dioxin residue.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Inquiries by aircrew veterans in 2011 brought a decision by the U.S.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Department of Veterans Affairs opining that not enough dioxin residue remained to injure these post-Vietnam War veterans.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Center For Disease Control's Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease Registry challenged this with their finding that former spray aircraft were indeed contaminated and the aircrews exposed to harmful levels of dioxin.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In response to veterans' concerns, the VA in February 2014 referred the C-123 issue to the Institute of Medicine for a special study, with results released on January 9, 2015.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In 1978, the EPA suspended spraying of Agent Orange in national forests.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Agent Orange was sprayed on thousands of acres of brush in the Tennessee Valley for 15 years before scientists discovered the herbicide was dangerous.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Monroe County, Tennessee, is one of the locations known to have been sprayed according to the Tennessee Valley Authority.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Forty-four remote acres were sprayed with Agent Orange along power lines throughout the National Forest.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In 1983, New Jersey declared a Passaic River production site to be a state of emergency.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The dioxin pollution in the Passaic River dates back to the Vietnam era, when Diamond Alkali manufactured it in a factory along the river.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The tidal river carried dioxin upstream and down, contaminating a 17 mi (27 km) stretch of riverbed in one of New Jersey's most populous areas.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] A December 2006 Department of Defense report listed Agent Orange testing, storage, and disposal sites at 32 locations throughout the United States, Canada, Thailand, Puerto Rico, Korea, and in the Pacific Ocean.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The Veteran Administration has also acknowledged that Agent Orange was used domestically by U.S. forces in test sites throughout the United States.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Eglin Air Force Base in Florida was one of the primary testing sites throughout the 1960s.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In February 2012, Monsanto agreed to settle a case covering dioxin contamination around a plant in Nitro, West Virginia, that had manufactured Agent Orange.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Monsanto agreed to pay up to $9 million for cleanup of affected homes, $84 million for medical monitoring of people affected, and the community's legal fees.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] On 9 August 2012, the United States and Vietnam began a cooperative cleaning up of the toxic chemical on part of Da Nang International Airport, marking the first time the U.S. government has been involved in cleaning up Agent Orange in Vietnam.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Danang was the primary storage site of the chemical.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Two other cleanup sites the United States and Vietnam are looking at is Biên Hòa, in the southern province of Đồng Nai is a hotspot for dioxin and so is Phù Cát airport in the central province of Bình Định, says U.S.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] According to the Vietnamese newspaper *Nhân Dân*, the U.S. government provided $41 million to the project.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The Naval Construction Battalion Center at Gulfport, Mississippi was the largest storage site in the United States for Agent Orange.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] It was about 30 acres (12 ha) in size and was still being cleaned up in 2013.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] In 2016, the EPA laid out its plan for cleaning up an 8 mi (13 km) stretch of the Passaic River in New Jersey, with an estimated cost of $1.4 billion.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] The contaminants reached to Newark Bay and other waterways, according to the EPA, which has designated the area a Superfund site.
[src:air-quality-index/agent-orange-p02] Since destruction of the dioxin requires high temperatures over 1,000 °C (1,830 °F), the destruction process is energy intensive.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] An **air quality index** (**AQI**) is an approximation of how polluted the air currently is or how polluted it is forecast to become.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] As air pollution levels rise, so does the AQI, along with the associated public health risks.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Different countries have their own air quality indices, corresponding to different national air quality standards.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] These include Canada's Air Quality Health Index, Malaysia's Air Pollution Index, and Singapore's Pollutant Standards Index.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Pollutants that are commonly monitored include ground-level ozone, particulates, sulfur dioxide, carbon monoxide, and nitrogen dioxide.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Children, the elderly, and individuals with respiratory or cardiovascular problems are typically the first groups affected by poor air quality.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] When the AQI is high, governmental bodies generally encourage people to reduce physical activity outdoors, or even avoid going out altogether.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Computation of the AQI requires an air pollutant concentration over a specified averaging period, obtained from an air monitor or model.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Taken together, concentration and time represent the dose of the air pollutant.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Health effects corresponding to a given dose are established by epidemiological research.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Air pollutants vary in potency, and the function used to convert from air pollutant concentration to AQI varies by pollutant.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Its air-quality index values are typically grouped into ranges.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Each range is assigned a descriptor, a color code, and a standardized public health advisory.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The AQI can increase due to an increase of air emissions.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] For example, during rush hour traffic, or when there is an upwind forest fire or from a lack of dilution of air pollutants.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Stagnant air, often caused by an anticyclone, temperature inversion, or low wind speeds lets air pollution remain in a local area, leading to high concentrations of pollutants, chemical reactions between air contaminants and hazy conditions.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Most air contaminants do not have an associated AQI.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Many countries monitor ground-level ozone, particulates, sulfur dioxide, carbon monoxide and, nitrogen dioxide, and calculate air quality indices for these pollutants.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The definition of the AQI in a particular nation reflects the discourse surrounding the development of national air-quality standards in that nation.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] A website allowing government agencies anywhere in the world to submit their real-time air monitoring data for display using a common definition of the air quality index has recently become available.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Each of the states and territories of Australia is responsible for monitoring air-quality and publishing data in accordance with the National Environment Protection (Ambient Air Quality) Measure (NEPM) standards.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Each state and territory publishes air- quality data for individual monitoring locations, and most states and territories publish air -quality indexes for each monitoring location.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Across Australia, a consistent approach is taken with air-quality indexes, using a simple linear scale where 100 represents the maximum concentration standard for each pollutant, as set by the NEPM.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The air quality index (AQI) for an individual location is simply the highest of the air quality index values for each pollutant being monitored at that location.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Air quality in Canada has been reported for many years with provincial air-quality indices (AQIs).
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Significantly, AQI values reflect air quality management objectives, which are based on the lowest achievable emissions rate, rather than exclusive concern for human health.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The Air Quality Health Index (AQHI) is a scale designed to help understand the effect of air quality on health.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] It is a health protection tool used to make decisions to reduce short-term exposure to air pollution by adjusting activity levels during increased levels of air pollution.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The Air Quality Health Index also provides advice on how to improve air quality by proposing a behavioral change to reduce the environmental footprint.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] This index pays particular attention to people who are sensitive to air pollution.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] It provides them with advice on how to protect their health during air quality levels associated with *low*, *moderate*, *high* and *very high* health risks.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The AQHI provides a number from 1 to 10+ to indicate the level of health risk associated with local air quality.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] On occasion, when the amount of air pollution is abnormally high, the number may exceed 10.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The AQHI provides a local air-quality current value as well as a local air quality maximums forecast for today, tonight, and tomorrow, and provides associated health advice.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] On December 30, 2013, Hong Kong replaced the Air Pollution Index with a new index called the *Air Quality Health Index*.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] This index, reported by the Environmental Protection Department, is measured on a scale of 1 to 10+, and considers four air pollutants: ozone; nitrogen dioxide; sulfur dioxide and particulate matter (including PM10 and PM2.5).
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] For any given hour the AQHI is calculated from the sum of the percentage excess risk of daily hospital admissions attributable to the 3-hour moving average concentrations of these four pollutants.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] China's Ministry of Environmental Protection (MEP) is responsible for measuring the level of air pollution in China.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] As of January 1, 2013, MEP monitors daily pollution level in 163 of its major cities.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The score for each pollutant is non-linear, as is the final AQI score.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Thus an AQI of 300 does not mean twice the pollution of AQI at 150, nor does it mean the air is twice as harmful.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The concentration of a pollutant when its IAQI is 100 does not equal twice its concentration when its IAQI is 50, nor does it mean the pollutant is twice as harmful.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] While an AQI of 50 from day 1 to 182 and AQI of 100 from day 183 to 365 does provide an annual average of 75, it does not mean the pollution is acceptable even if the benchmark of 100 is deemed safe.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Because the benchmark is a 24-hour target, and the annual average must match the annual target, it is entirely possible to have safe air every day of the year but still fail the annual pollution benchmark.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The *Common Air Quality Index* (CAQI) is an air quality index used in Europe since 2006.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] In November 2017, the European Environment Agency announced the *European Air Quality Index* (EAQI) and started encouraging its use on websites and for other ways of informing the public about air quality.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] As of 2012, the EU-supported project *CiteairII* argued that the CAQI had been evaluated on a "large set" of data, and described the CAQI's motivation and definition.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] *CiteairII* stated that having an air quality index that would be easy to present to the general public was a major motivation, leaving aside the more complex question of a health-based index, which would require, for example, effects of combined levels of different pollutants.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The main aim of the CAQI was to have an index that would encourage wide comparison across the EU, without replacing local indices.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The CAQI is a number on a scale from 0 to 100, where a low value means good air quality and a high value means poor air quality.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The index is defined in both hourly and daily versions, and separately near roads (a "roadside" or "traffic" index) or away from roads (a "background" index).
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] As of 2012, the CAQI had two mandatory components for the roadside index, NO2 and PM10, and three mandatory components for the background index, NO2, PM10 and O3.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] It also included optional pollutants PM2.5, CO and SO2.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] A "sub-index" is calculated for each of the mandatory (and optional if available) components.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The CAQI is defined as the sub-index that represents the worst quality among those components.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Some of the key pollutant concentrations in μg/m3 for the hourly background index, the corresponding sub-indices, and five CAQI ranges and verbal descriptions are as follows.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Frequently updated CAQI values and maps are shown on www.airqualitynow.eu and other websites.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] A separate *Year Average Common Air Quality Index* (YACAQI) is also defined, in which different pollutant sub-indices are separately normalised to a value typically near unity.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] For example, the yearly averages of NO2, PM10 and PM2.5 are divided by 40 μg/m3, 40 μg/m3 and 20 μg/m3, respectively.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The overall background or traffic YACAQI for a city is the arithmetic mean of a defined subset of these sub-indices.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The National Air Quality Index (NAQI) was launched in New Delhi on 17 September 2014, under the Swachh Bharat Abhiyan.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The Central Pollution Control Board along with State Pollution Control Boards has been operating National Air Monitoring Programme (NAMP) covering 240 cities of the country, with more than 342 monitoring stations.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] An Expert Group comprising medical professionals, air quality experts, academia, advocacy groups, and SPCBs was constituted and a technical study was awarded to IIT Kanpur.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] IIT Kanpur and the Expert Group recommended an AQI scheme in 2014.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] While the earlier measuring index was limited to three indicators, the new index measures eight parameters.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The continuous monitoring systems that provide data on near real-time basis are installed in New Delhi, Mumbai, Pune, Kolkata and Ahmedabad.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] There are six NAQI categories, namely *Good*, *Satisfactory*, *Moderate*, *Poor*, *Severe* and *Hazardous*.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The proposed NAQI will consider eight pollutants PM10, PM2.5, NO2, SO2, CO, O3, NH3, and Pb) for which short-term (up to 24-hourly averaging period) National Ambient Air Quality Standards are prescribed.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Based on the measured ambient concentrations, corresponding standards and likely health effects, a sub-index is calculated for each of these pollutants.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The worst sub-index reflects overall NAQI.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Likely health effects for different NAQI categories and pollutants have also been suggested, with primary inputs from the medical experts in the group.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] According to Japan Weather Association, Japan uses a different scale to measure the air quality index.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The air quality in Mexico City is reported in IMECAs.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The IMECA is calculated using the measurements of average times of the chemicals ozone (O3), sulfur dioxide (SO2), nitrogen dioxide (NO2), carbon monoxide (CO), particles smaller than 2.5 micrometers (PM2.5), and particles smaller than 10 micrometers (PM10).
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Singapore uses the Pollutant Standards Index to report on its air quality, with details of the calculation similar but not identical to those used in Malaysia and Hong Kong.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The PSI chart below is grouped by index values and descriptors, according to the National Environment Agency.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The Ministry of Environment of South Korea uses the Comprehensive Air-quality Index (CAI) to describe the ambient air quality based on the health risks of air pollution.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The index aims to help the public easily understand the air quality and protect people's health.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The CAI is on a scale from 0 to 500, which is divided into six categories.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The higher the CAI value, the greater the level of air pollution.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Of values of the five air pollutants, the highest is the CAI value.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The index also has associated health effects and a colour representation of the categories as shown below.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The N Seoul Tower on Namsan Mountain in central Seoul, South Korea, is illuminated in blue, from sunset to 23:00 and 22:00 in winter, on days where the air quality in Seoul is 45 or less.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] During the spring of 2012, the Tower was lit up for 52 days, which is four days more than in 2011.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The most commonly used air quality index in the UK is the *Daily Air Quality Index* recommended by the Committee on the Medical Effects of Air Pollutants (COMEAP).
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] This index has ten points, which are further grouped into four bands: low, moderate, high and very high.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Each of the bands comes with advice for at-risk groups and the general population.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The index is based on the concentrations of five pollutants.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The index is calculated from the concentrations of the following pollutants: ozone, nitrogen dioxide, sulfur dioxide, PM2.5 and PM10.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The breakpoints between index values are defined for each pollutant separately and the overall index is defined as the maximum value of the index.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Different averaging periods are used for different pollutants.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) has developed an Air Quality Index that is used to report air quality.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] An AQI value over 300 represents hazardous air quality and below 50 the air quality is good.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] This AQI is divided into six categories indicating increasing levels of health concern.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The AQI is based on the five "criteria" pollutants regulated under the Clean Air Act: ground-level ozone, particulate matter, carbon monoxide, sulfur dioxide, and nitrogen dioxide.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The EPA has established National Ambient Air Quality Standards (NAAQS) for each of these pollutants in order to protect public health.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] An AQI value of 100 generally corresponds to the level of the NAAQS for the pollutant.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The Clean Air Act (USA) (1990) requires the EPA to review its National Ambient Air Quality Standards every five years to reflect evolving health effects information.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The Air Quality Index is adjusted periodically to reflect these changes.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] To convert an air pollutant concentration to an AQI, EPA has developed a calculator.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] If multiple pollutants are measured at a monitoring site, then the largest or "dominant" AQI value is reported for the location.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The ozone AQI between 100 and 300 is computed by selecting the larger of the AQI calculated with a 1-hour ozone value and the AQI computed with the 8-hour ozone value.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Eight-hour ozone averages do not define AQI values greater than 300; AQI values of 301 or greater are calculated with 1-hour ozone concentrations.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] 1-hour SO2 values do not define higher AQI values greater than 200.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] AQI values of 201 or greater are calculated with 24-hour SO2 concentrations.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Real-time monitoring data from continuous monitors are typically available as 1-hour averages.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] However, computation of the AQI for some pollutants requires averaging over multiple hours of data.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] For reporting the PM2.5, PM10 and ozone air quality indices, this surrogate concentration is called the NowCast.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] The Nowcast is a particular type of weighted average that provides more weight to the most recent air quality data when air pollution levels are changing.
[src:air-quality-index/air-quality-index] Real time monitoring data and forecasts of air quality that are color-coded in terms of the air quality index are available from EPA's AirNow web site.
